# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: age-of-discovery
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:age-of-discovery/180th-meridian] The **180th meridian** or **antimeridian** is the meridian 180° both east and west of the prime meridian in a geographical coordinate system.
[src:age-of-discovery/180th-meridian] The longitude at this line can be given as either east or west.
[src:age-of-discovery/180th-meridian] On Earth, the prime and 180th meridians form a great ellipse that divides the planet into the Western and Eastern Hemispheres.
[src:age-of-discovery/180th-meridian] The antimeridian passes mostly through the open waters of the Pacific Ocean but also runs across land in Russia, Fiji, and Antarctica.
[src:age-of-discovery/180th-meridian] An important function of this meridian is its use as the basis for the International Date Line, which snakes around national borders to maintain date consistency within the territories of Russia, the United States, Kiribati, Fiji and New Zealand.
[src:age-of-discovery/180th-meridian] The only places where roads cross this meridian are in Fiji and Russia.
[src:age-of-discovery/180th-meridian] Fiji has several such roads and some buildings very close to it.
[src:age-of-discovery/180th-meridian] Russia has three roads in the Chukotka Autonomous Okrug.
[src:age-of-discovery/180th-meridian] Many geographic software libraries or data formats project the world to a rectangle; very often this rectangle is split exactly at the 180th meridian.
[src:age-of-discovery/180th-meridian] This often makes it non-trivial to do simple tasks (like representing an area, or a line) over the 180th meridian.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] The Great Barrier Reef Expedition was a scientific study suggested by Sir Matthew Nathan and Professor Henry Richards who led the Australian Great Barrier Reef Committee from its establishment in 1922.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] With support from the British Barrier Reef Committee and the Association for the Advancement of Science in England, there was considerable interest in conducting zoological studies of Australia's Great Barrier Reef, to investigate theories put forward by Charles Darwin and others.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] It was also planned to determine the economic importance of the reef's marine life.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] This largely British expedition of scientists sought financial support from the Australian government, universities and the public to fund the expedition and study biological and geological life in a number of sections of the Reef.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] Maurice Yonge, a marine invertebrate researcher, was encouraged to join a proposed expedition to Australia's Great Barrier Reef in 1927.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] Others included James Steers, lecturer in geomorphology who acted as the expedition's surveyor.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] He was assisted by Michael Spender and E.C.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] Otter and Aubrey Nicholls would be assistants, and Frank Moorhouse of the University of Queensland would provide local marine biology knowledge.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] They arrived at the two islands of Low Isles on 16 July 1928 and encamped there for thirteen months.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] Sidnie Manton and Elizabeth Fraser would join the expedition for four months and work with the shore party.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] The expedition was unique in its inclusion of female researchers.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] The Australian Museum also sent five people to help with the research throughout the year – Tom Iredale, Gilbert Whitley, William Boardman, Arthur Livingstone and Frank McNeill.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] Indigenous workers were hired from the nearby Anglican mission at Yarrabah to work on Low Isles in support of the team.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] They included Andy and Grace Dabah who worked as handyman and cook and were later replaced by Claude and Minnie Connolly.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] The children of the Dabah and Connolly families also lived with their parents during the time they supported the expedition.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] Harry Mossman and Paul Sexton from Yarrabah were hired as crew on the research vessel Luana.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] The Luana was used to carry out scientific studies on and in the water as well as carry provisions to and from the mainland.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] The expedition was divided into four parts.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] Researchers investigated ocean conditions, taking hydrographic measurements, recording meteorological and tidal data and monitored plankton.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] They observed the growth rate of the corals and the marine life around it.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] They collected specimens including plankton as well as conducting dredging and trawling around the reef.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] Trochus shell was collected and studied and at the time a trochus farming industry was proposed.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] Black-Lip pearl oysters, Beche De Mer and rock and mangrove oysters, as well as the fish populations of the surrounding areas were assessed for potential economic development.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] Other studies considered a sardine fishing industry for the region and the turtle industry of Heron Island, near Gladstone.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] Boring of the reef had been undertaken around Michaelmas Cay in 1926 to determine the age and thickness of the reef, which helped the geological research.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] The scientific discoveries of the expedition were well reported in the press during 1928–1929.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] One of the first visitors to Low Isles during the Expedition was journalist Charles Barrett whose newspaper articles were later published as a book.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] The expedition itself published seven volumes of scientific material in addition to articles in scholarly journals.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] Maurice Yonge also published a book aimed at a general audience – *A year on the Great Barrier Reef* (1930).
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] In part due to the extensive newspaper coverage, tourists sought out the islands following the expedition to collect shells and corals.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] This collecting for scientific and private collections was so extreme that the island was ‘virtually swept clean’.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] Yonge and his team's research pioneered studies into coral physiology and their research persists in being vital reference material to current study.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] In 1968 a Belgian expedition to the reef was undertaken.
[src:age-of-discovery/1928-great-barrier-reef-expedition] In 1973, a Royal Society and Universities of Queensland Expedition was undertaken to the northern part of the reef.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The **1948 Palestine war** (30 November 1947 – 10 March 1949) was fought in the territory of what had been, at the start of the war, British-ruled Mandatory Palestine.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] During the war, Zionist forces conquered about 78% of the former territory of the mandate, causing the expulsion and flight of over 700,000 Palestinians.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Transjordan took control of the territory west of the Jordan River and Egypt occupied the coastal territory around Gaza.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The war formally ended with the 1949 Armistice Agreements, which established the Green Line *de facto* borders of the State of Israel, the West Bank, and the Gaza Strip.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] It was the first war of the Israeli–Palestinian conflict and the broader Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The war had two main phases, the first being the 1947–1948 civil war, which began on 30 November 1947, a day after the United Nations voted to adopt the Partition Plan for Palestine, which planned for the division of the territory into Jewish and Arab sovereign states.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] During this period, the British still maintained a declining rule over Palestine and occasionally intervened in the violence.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Initially on the defensive, the Zionist forces switched to the offensive in April 1948.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In anticipation of an invasion by Arab armies, they enacted Plan Dalet, an operation aimed at securing territory for the establishment of a Jewish state.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The second phase of the war began on 14 May 1948, with the declaration of the establishment of the State of Israel and the termination of the British Mandate at midnight.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The following morning, the surrounding Arab armies invaded Palestine, beginning the 1948 Arab–Israeli War.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Egyptians advanced in the south-east while the Jordanian Arab Legion and Iraqi forces captured the central highlands.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Syria and Lebanon fought against the Israeli forces in the north.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The newly formed Israel Defense Forces managed to halt the Arab forces and in the following months began pushing them back and capturing territory.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] During the war, massacres and acts of terror were conducted by both sides.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] A campaign of massacres and violence against the Arab population, such as occurred at Lydda and Ramle and the Battle of Haifa, led to the expulsion and flight of over 700,000 Palestinians, with most of their urban areas being depopulated and destroyed.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] This violence and dispossession is remembered by Palestinians as the Nakba (Arabic for "the catastrophe") and resulted in the beginning of the Palestinian refugee problem.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Hundreds of thousands of Jews fled or were expelled from Arab states in the three years following the Arab defeat in the war, over 260,000 of which settled in Israel.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Zionism formed in Europe as the national movement of the Jewish people.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] It sought to reestablish Jewish statehood in the ancient homeland.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The first wave of Zionist immigration, dubbed the First Aliyah, lasted from 1882 to 1903.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Some 30,000 Jews, mostly from the Russian Empire, reached Ottoman Palestine.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] They were driven both by the Zionist idea and by the wave of antisemitism in Europe, especially in the Russian Empire, which came in the form of brutal pogroms.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] They wanted to establish Jewish agricultural settlements and a Jewish majority in the land that would allow them to gain statehood.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Arab inhabitants of Ottoman Palestine who saw the Zionist Jews of the first aliyah settle next to them were not associated with a national movement at the end of the 19th century.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Historically, Palestine had never been administered or recognized as a distinct province by any of its Muslim rulers.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Starting in 1882, the Ottomans issued a stream of "restrictive orders" against Jewish settlement and land purchases in Palestine.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] However, as a result of its perceived insignificance and the inefficiency of Ottoman bureaucracies, these restrictions had little effect.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Until the 1910s, Zionists encountered little violence, as the Arabs lacked political awareness and were disorganized.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Between 1909 and 1914, this changed, as Arabs killed 12 Jewish settlement guards and Arab nationalism, and opposition to the Zionist enterprise, increased.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In 1911, Arabs attempted to thwart the establishment of a Jewish settlement in the Jezreel Valley, and the dispute resulted in the death of one Arab man and a Jewish guard.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Arabs called the Jews the "new Crusaders", and anti-Zionist (and, occasionally, anti-Semitic) rhetoric flourished.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] During the war, Palestine served as the frontline between the Ottoman Empire and the British Empire in Egypt.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The war briefly halted Jewish-Arab friction.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The British invaded the land in 1915 and 1916 after two unsuccessful Ottoman attacks on Sinai.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] They were assisted by the Arab tribes in Hejaz, led by the Hashemites, and promised them sovereignty over the Arab areas of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Palestine was excluded from the promise, initially intended to be a joint British-French domain.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Zionist lobbying, led by Chaim Weizmann, played a significant role, along with religious and humanitarian motivations.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The fact that the Arabs of Palestine supported the Ottoman fight against the Allied Powers also contributed.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Additionally, the British believed that a British-backed state would help defend the Suez Canal.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] At that time, the Arab Hashemites did not seem opposed to Jewish rule over Palestine.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] After World War I, the League of Nations granted Britain the Mandate for Palestine, which required it to implement the Balfour Declaration.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] As the numbers and strength of the Yishuv (the Jewish community in Palestine) grew, tensions between the Jewish and Arab communities deepened.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Significant bouts of violence happened during the 1920 Jerusalem Riots, as well as in 1921 and 1929.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In addition to the emerging Palestinian Arab nationalism, the violence also drew on religious inspirations, such as the accusation that the Jews intended to take over the Temple Mount.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Despite Arab opposition to Jewish immigration, leading Palestinian families continued to sell land to Zionists throughout the period.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] At least one quarter of members of the Palestinian Arab Executive benefited financially from such purchases, including the mayor of Jerusalem and the al-Husayni family.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Zionist leaders intermittently attempted to reach a compromise with the Arabs, but none proved possible.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The peasant-led 1936–1939 Arab revolt in Palestine broke out in the context of increased Jewish migration to Palestine and the plight of the rural native *fallāḥīn*.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] It sparked following the murder of three Jewish drivers on April 15, 1936, whose funeral led rapidly spreading disturbances.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The revolt began with a general strike among Palestinian Arabs on April 19, 1936, which escalated into intercommunal violence.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The brutal suppression of the revolt by the British significantly weakened the Palestinian Arabs in advance of the 1948 war.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Particularly after the White Paper of 1939, the Zionist paramilitary organizations Irgun, Lehi, and Haganah carried out a campaign of acts of terror and sabotage against British rule.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Among these attacks was the 1946 King David Hotel bombing carried out by the Irgun which killed 91 people.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Following World War II, the surrounding Arab states were emerging from mandatory rule.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Transjordan, under the Hashemite ruler Abdullah I, gained independence from Britain in 1946 and was called Jordan in 1949, but remained under heavy British influence.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Egypt gained nominal independence in 1922, but Britain continued to exert a strong influence on it until the Anglo-Egyptian Treaty of 1936 limited Britain's presence to a garrison of troops on the Suez Canal until 1945.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Lebanon became an independent state in 1943, but French troops did not withdraw until 1946, the same year Syria won its independence from France.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In 1945, at British prompting, Egypt, Iraq, Lebanon, Saudi Arabia, Syria, Transjordan, and Yemen formed the Arab League to coordinate policy among the Arab states.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Iraq and Transjordan coordinated closely, signing a mutual defence treaty, while Egypt, Syria, and Saudi Arabia feared that Transjordan would annex part or all of Palestine and use it as a stepping stone to attack or undermine Syria, Lebanon, and the Hijaz.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] This was an attempt to resolve the Arab-Jewish conflict by partitioning Palestine into "Independent Arab and Jewish States and the Special International Regime for the City of Jerusalem".
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Each state would comprise three major sections; the Arab state would also have an enclave in Jaffa, which had an Arab-majority population and provided the Arab state with a port on the Mediterranean.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] With about 32% of the population, the Jews were allocated 56% of the territory (most of it the Negev desert).
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Palestinian Arabs were allocated 42% of the land, which had a population of 818,000 Palestinian Arabs and 10,000 Jews.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In consideration of its religious significance, the Jerusalem area, including Bethlehem, with 100,000 Jews and an equal number of Palestinian Arabs, was to become a *corpus separatum*, to be administered by the UN.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The residents in the UN-administered territory were given the right to choose to be citizens of either of the new states.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Jewish leadership accepted the partition plan as "the indispensable minimum", glad to gain international recognition but sorry that they did not receive more.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The representatives of the Palestinian Arabs and the Arab League firmly opposed the UN action and rejected its authority in the matter, arguing that the partition plan was unfair to the Arabs because of the population balance at that time.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] According to the Israeli historian Benny Morris, the Arabs rejected the partition, not because it was supposedly unfair, but because their leaders rejected any form of partition.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] They held "that the rule of Palestine should revert to its inhabitants, in accordance with the provisions of ... the Charter of the United Nations".
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] According to Article 73b of the Charter, the UN should develop self-government of the peoples in a territory under its administration.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In the immediate aftermath of the UN's approval of the partition plan, explosions of joy in the Jewish community were counterbalanced by discontent in the Arab community.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Soon after, violence broke out and became more prevalent.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Murders, reprisals, and counter-reprisals came fast upon each other, resulting in dozens killed on both sides.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The sanguinary impasse persisted as no force intervened to put a stop to the escalating violence.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The first phase of the war took place from the United Nations General Assembly vote for the Partition Plan for Palestine on 29 November 1947 until the termination of the British Mandate and Israeli proclamation of statehood on 14 May 1948.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] During this period the Jewish and Arab communities of the British Mandate clashed, while the British organised their withdrawal and intervened only occasionally.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In the first two months of the Civil War, around 1,000 people were killed and 2,000 injured, and by the end of March, the figure had risen to 2,000 dead and 4,000 wounded.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] These figures correspond to an average of more than 100 deaths and 200 casualties per week in a population of 2,000,000.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] From January onwards, operations became increasingly militarised.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] A number of Arab Liberation Army regiments infiltrated Palestine, each active in a variety of distinct sectors around the coastal towns.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] They consolidated their presence in Galilee and Samaria.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Army of the Holy War, under Abd al-Qadir al-Husayni's command, came from Egypt with several hundred men.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Having recruited a few thousand volunteers, al-Husayni organised the blockade of the 100,000 Jewish residents of Jerusalem.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] To counter this, the Yishuv authorities tried to supply the city with convoys of up to 100 armoured vehicles, but the operation became more and more impractical as the number of casualties in the relief convoys surged.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] By March, al-Husayni's tactic had paid off.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Almost all of Haganah's armoured vehicles had been destroyed, the blockade was in full operation, and hundreds of Haganah members who had tried to bring supplies into the city were killed.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The situation for those in the Jewish settlements in the highly isolated Negev and North of Galilee was more critical.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] This caused the US to withdraw its support for the Partition Plan, and the Arab League began to believe that the Palestinian Arabs, reinforced by the Arab Liberation Army, could end the partition.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The British decided on 7 February 1948 to support Transjordan's annexation of the Arab part of Palestine.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] While the Jewish population was ordered to hold their ground everywhere at all costs, the Arab population was disrupted by general conditions of insecurity.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Up to 100,000 Arabs from the urban upper and middle classes in Haifa, Jaffa and Jerusalem, or Jewish-dominated areas, evacuated abroad or to Arab centres to the east.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] David Ben-Gurion ordered Yigal Yadin to plan for the announced intervention of the Arab states.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The result of his analysis was Plan Dalet, which was put in place at the start of April, and which marked the war's second phase, in which the Haganah took the offensive.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The first operation, Nachshon, was directed at lifting the blockade on Jerusalem.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In the last week of March, 136 supply trucks had tried to reach Jerusalem; only 41 had made it.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Arab attacks on communications and roads had intensified.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The convoys' failure and the loss of Jewish armoured vehicles had shaken the Yishuv leaders' confidence.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The city's food and water supply was cut off.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Jerusalem was on the verge of starvation in May, both food and water rationing had been introduced.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] During this time, paramilitary groups Irgun and Lehi, supported by the Haganah and Palmach, perpetrated the Deir Yassin massacre, killing at least 107 Arab villagers, including women and children, and expelled the rest of the village's residents (approximately 750 people).
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The event was widely publicized and had a deep effect on the Arab population's morale, greatly contributing to the Palestinian expulsion and flight.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Hadassah medical convoy massacre was conducted by Arab forces as retaliation for Deir Yassin.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] 79 Jews were killed in the attack which led to a further deterioration of Jewish-Arab relations.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] From April 4–15, the first large-scale operation of the Arab Liberation Army ended in a debacle, as they were roundly defeated at Mishmar HaEmek.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Their Druze allies left them through defection.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] As part of Plan Dalet, the Haganah, Palmach and Irgun captured the urban centers of Tiberias, Haifa (See: Battle of Haifa), Safed, Beisan, Jaffa, and Acre, violently expelling more than 250,000 Palestinian Arabs.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The British had essentially withdrawn their troops.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The situation pushed the neighbouring Arab states to intervene, but their preparation was not completed, and they could not assemble sufficient forces to turn the tide of the war.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The majority of Palestinian Arab hopes lay with the Arab Legion of Transjordan's monarch, King Abdullah I.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] However Abdullah did not intend to create a Palestinian state, but hoped to annex much of Eastern Palestine.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Playing both sides, he was in contact with both the Israelis and the Arab League.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Preparing for Arab intervention from neighbouring states, Haganah successfully launched Operations Yiftah and Ben-'Ami to secure the Jewish settlements of Galilee, and Operation Kilshon.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] This created an Israeli-controlled front around Jerusalem.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The inconclusive meeting between Golda Meir and Abdullah I, followed by the Kfar Etzion massacre on 13 May by the Arab Legion, led to predictions that the battle for Jerusalem would be merciless.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Israeli historians Benny Morris and Benjamin Kedar revealed that during the 1948 war, Israel conducted a biological warfare operation codenamed *Cast Thy Bread*, using typhoid bacteria to contaminate wells in Arab areas to prevent reentry and deter advancing Arab forces.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] On 14 May 1948, the day before the expiration of the British Mandate, David Ben-Gurion declared the establishment of a Jewish state in Eretz Israel, to be known as the State of Israel.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Palestinians' Arab Higher Committee rejected the Partition Resolution and any kind of Jewish state and refused to negotiate with "the Zionist Project".
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Over the next few days, contingents of four of the seven countries of the Arab League at that time, Egypt, Iraq, Transjordan, and Syria, invaded the former British Mandate of Palestine and fought the Israelis.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] They were supported by the Arab Liberation Army, Muslim Brotherhood contingents, and corps of volunteers from Saudi Arabia, Lebanon and Yemen.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Arab armies launched a simultaneous offensive on all fronts: Egyptian forces invaded from the south, Jordanian and Iraqi forces from the east, and Syrian forces invaded from the north.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Cooperation among the various Arab armies was poor.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The UN declared a truce on 29 May, which began on 11 June and lasted 28 days.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The ceasefire was overseen by UN mediator Folke Bernadotte and a team of UN Observers, army officers from Belgium, United States, Sweden and France.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Bernadotte was voted in by the General Assembly to "assure the safety of the holy places, to safeguard the well being of the population, and to promote 'a peaceful adjustment of the future situation of Palestine'".
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] He spoke of "peace by Christmas" but saw that the Arab world had continued to reject the existence of a Jewish state, whatever its borders.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] An arms embargo was declared with the intention that neither side would make gains from the truce.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Neither side respected the truce; both found ways around the restrictions.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Both the Israelis and the Arabs used this time to improve their positions, a direct violation of the terms of the ceasefire.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] "The Arabs violated the truce by reinforcing their lines with fresh units (including six companies of Sudanese regulars, a Saudi battalion and contingents from Yemen and Morocco) and by preventing supplies from reaching isolated Israeli settlements; occasionally, they opened fire along the lines".
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Israeli Defense Forces acquired weapons from Czechoslovakia in contravention to the terms of the truce, improving the training of its forces, and reorganising the army.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Yitzhak Rabin, an IDF commander who would later become Israel's fifth prime minister, said, "[w]ithout the arms from Czechoslovakia... it is very doubtful whether we would have been able to conduct the war".
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] As well as violating the arms and personnel embargo, both sides sent fresh units to the front.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Israel's army increased its manpower from approximately 30,000 or 35,000 men to almost 65,000 during the truce and its arms supply to "more than twenty-five thousand rifles, five thousand machine guns, and more than fifty million bullets".
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] As the truce began, a British officer stationed in Haifa said the four-week-long truce "would certainly be exploited by the Jews to continue military training and reorganization while the Arabs would waste [them] feuding over the future divisions of the spoils".
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] On 7 July, the day before the truce expired, Egyptian forces under General Muhammad Naguib renewed the war by attacking Negba.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Israeli forces launched a simultaneous offensive on all three fronts: Dani, Dekel, and Kedem.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The fighting was dominated by large-scale Israeli offensives and a defensive Arab posture and continued for ten days until the UN Security Council issued the Second Truce on 18 July.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Israeli Operation Dani resulted in the expulsion from Lydda and Ramle of 60,000 Palestinian residents.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] According to Benny Morris, in Ben-Gurion's view, Ramlah and Lydda constituted a special danger because their proximity might encourage cooperation between the Egyptian army, which had started its attack on Kibbutz Negbah, and the Arab Legion, which had taken the Lydda police station.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Widespread looting took place during these operations, and about 100,000 Palestinians became refugees.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In Operation Dekel, Nazareth was captured on 16 July.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In Operation Brosh, Israel tried and failed to drive the Syrian army out of northeastern Galilee.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] By the time the second truce took effect at 19:00 18 July, Israel had taken the lower Galilee from Haifa Bay to the Sea of Galilee.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] With smuggled Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress planes acquired in violation of the international arms embargo, Israel bombed a residential neighborhood in Cairo on July 15.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] At 19:00 on 18 July, the second truce of the conflict went into effect after intense diplomatic efforts by the UN.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] On 16 September, a new partition plan for Palestine was proposed but it was rejected by both sides.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] During the truce, the Egyptians regularly blocked the passage of supply convoys to the beleaguered northern Negev settlements by firing on them, contrary to the truce terms.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] On 15 October, they attacked another supply convoy, and the already planned Operation Yoav was launched.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Its goal was to drive a wedge between the Egyptian forces along the coast and the Beersheba-Hebron-Jerusalem road, and to open the road to the encircled Negev settlements.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Yoav was headed by Southern Front commander Yigal Allon.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The operation was a success, shattering the Egyptian army ranks and forcing Egyptian forces to retreat from the northern Negev, Beersheba, and Ashdod.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Meanwhile, on 19 October, Operation Ha-Har commenced operations in the Jerusalem Corridor.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] On 22 October, the third truce went into effect.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Before dawn on 22 October, in defiance of the UN Security Council ceasefire order, ALA units stormed the IDF hilltop position of Sheikh Abd, overlooking Kibbutz Manara.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Ben-Gurion initially rejected Moshe Carmel's demand to launch a major counteroffensive.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] He was wary of antagonising the United Nations on the heels of its ceasefire order.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] During 24–25 October, ALA troops regularly sniped at Manara and traffic along the main road.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In contacts with UN observers, Fawzi al-Qawuqji demanded that Israel evacuate neighbouring Kibbutz Yiftah and thin out its forces in Manara.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The IDF demanded the ALA's withdrawal from the captured positions and, after a "no" from al-Qawuqji, informed the UN that it felt free to do as it pleased.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] On 24 October, the IDF launched Operation Hiram and captured the entire upper Galilee, originally attributed to the Arab state by the Partition Plan.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] At the end of the month, Israel had captured the whole Galilee and had advanced 5 miles (8.0 km) into Lebanon to the Litani River.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] On 22 December, large IDF forces started Operation Horev.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Its objective was to encircle the Egyptian Army in the Gaza Strip and force the Egyptians to end the war.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The operation was a decisive Israeli victory, and Israeli raids into the Nitzana area and the Sinai Peninsula forced the Egyptian army into the Gaza Strip, where it was surrounded.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Israeli forces withdrew from Sinai and Gaza under international pressure and after the British threatened to intervene against Israel.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Egyptian government announced on 6 January 1949 that it was willing to enter armistice negotiations.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Allon persuaded Ben-Gurion to continue as planned, but Ben-Gurion told him: "Do you know the value of peace talks with Egypt?
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] After all, that is our great dream!" He was sure that Transjordan and the other Arab states would follow suit.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] On 7 January 1949, a truce was achieved.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] On 5 March, Israel launched Operation Uvda; by 10 March, the Israelis reached Umm Rashrash (where Eilat was built later) and took it without a battle.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Negev Brigade and Golani Brigade took part in the operation.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] They raised a hand-made flag ("The Ink Flag") and claimed Umm Rashrash for Israel.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In 1949, Israel signed separate armistices with Egypt on 24 February, Lebanon on 23 March, Transjordan on 3 April, and Syria on 20 July.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The armistice lines saw Israel holding about 78% of Mandatory Palestine (as it stood after the independence of Transjordan in 1946), 22% more than the UN Partition Plan had allocated.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] These ceasefire lines were known afterwards as the "Green Line".
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Gaza Strip and the West Bank were occupied by Egypt and Transjordan, respectively.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The United Nations Truce Supervision Organization and Mixed Armistice Commissions were set up to monitor ceasefires, supervise the armistice agreements, to prevent isolated incidents from escalating, and assist other UN peacekeeping operations in the region.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Israel lost 6,373 people, about 1% of its population, in the war.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] About 4,000 were soldiers and the rest were civilians.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The exact number of Arab losses is unknown but is estimated at between 4,000 for Egypt (2,000), Jordan and Syria (1,000 each) and 15,000.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] During the 1947–48 Civil War in Mandatory Palestine and the 1948 Arab–Israeli War that followed, around 700,000 Palestinian Arabs fled or were expelled.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In 1951, the UN Conciliation Commission for Palestine estimated that the number of Palestinian refugees displaced from Israel was 711,000.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] This number did not include displaced Palestinians inside Israeli-held territory.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The list of villages depopulated during the Arab–Israeli conflict includes more than 400 Arab villages.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] It also includes about ten Jewish villages and neighbourhoods, resulting in no Jews left in or being able to return to the Arab-controlled territory.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The causes of the 1948 Palestinian exodus are a controversial topic among historians.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The Palestinian refugee problem and the debate around the right of their return are also major issues of the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Palestinians have staged annual demonstrations and protests on 15 May of each year.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] During the 1948 Arab–Israeli War, around 10,000 Jews were forced to evacuate their homes in Palestine or Israel.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The war indirectly resulted in the Jewish exodus from Arab and Muslim lands.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Largely because of the war between Jews and Arabs in Palestine, hundreds of thousands of Jews who lived in the Arab states were intimidated into flight, or were expelled from their native countries, most of them reaching Israel.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The immediate reasons for this exodus were both the popular Arab hostility, including pogroms and anti-Jewish governmental measures, as well as the desire of many Jewish people to join the newly established State of Israel.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In the three years following the war, about 700,000 Jews immigrated to Israel, where they were absorbed, fed and housed mainly along the borders and in former Palestinian lands.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Beginning in 1948, and continuing until 1972, an estimated 800,000 to 1,000,000 Jews migrated to Israel.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] From 1945 until the closure of 1952, more than 250,000 Jewish displaced persons lived in European refugee camps.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] About 136,000 of them immigrated to Israel.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] More than 270,000 Jews immigrated from Eastern Europe, mainly Romania and Poland (over 100,000 each).
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Overall 700,000 Jews settled in Israel, doubling its Jewish population.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Since the war, different historiographical traditions have interpreted the events of 1948 differently; in the words of the New Historian Avi Shlaim, "each side subscribes to a different version of events." In the Israeli narrative, the war is Israel's War of Independence.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In the Palestinian narrative, the War of 1948 is inextricable from the Nakba, the Zionist movement is one of settler colonialism, and the Israelis are seen as conquerors and the Palestinians as victims.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The different narratives of 1948 reflect these different perceptions.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] An issue affecting the historiography of 1948 is access to sources and archives, which may have been destroyed, appropriated, censored, or otherwise made unavailable to some or all researchers.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Linguistic barriers represent another hurdle, as most research is published exclusively in the author's native language and is not translated.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The historiography of 1948 is tied to political legitimacy in the present and has implications for the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The narratives of 1948 have also had implications for Palestinian refugees.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Being the victors, the Israelis "were able to propagate more effectively than their opponents their version of this fateful war", in the words of Avi Shlaim.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Only in 1987 was that narrative effectively challenged outside the Arab world.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] It also portrays Israelis as morally superior, lacks political analysis, and gives undue weight to "the heroic feats of the Israeli fighters." This nationalist narrative was taught in Israeli schools and used for gaining legitimacy internationally.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] These writers came to be known as New Historians or "post-Zionists".
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Among their most vitriolic critics was Shabtai Teveth, biographer of David Ben-Gurion, who published "The New Historians", a series of four weekly full-page articles attacking the new historians, in Haaretz May 1989.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Teveth claimed that the new historiography was flawed in its practice and that it was politically motived, that it was pro-Palestinian and aimed to delegitimize the State of Israel.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Ilan Pappé identifies a turn in predominant Israeli narratives about 1948 in September 2000.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In this period, the focus of Israeli historical writing on 1948 shifted largely from its human impact back to its military aspects.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Neo-Zionist writers were given selective access to top-secret material, to which writers critical of Zionism would not have been given access, and much of their work was published by the Israeli Ministry of Defense.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Among those Pappé associated with the neo-Zionist perspective were Benny Morris (who had become more outspokenly defensive of Zionism by this time), Daniel Gutwein, Mordechai Bar-On, Yoav Gelber, Tamir Goren, Arnon Golan, Alon Kadish, and Yoav Peleg, as well as the journal *Techelet*.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Yoav Gelber identifies Arif al-Arif's six volume *an-Nakba* written in Arabic in the 1950s as thorough and notable.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Palestinian narratives have focused on countering the dominant Zionist narrative; the preëminent Palestinian historian of 1948 Walid Khalidi has dedicated much of his career to disproving the official Israeli narrative that the 1948 Palestinian expulsion and flight was voluntary.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Without access to much in the way of archival materials, Palestinian historians have made use of oral history.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] In the narratives of the wider Arab-Muslim world, 1948 is seen as an "Arab debacle", representative of the region's social and political decline from its "glorious distant past".
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The American journalist Joan Peters' 1984 book *From Time Immemorial* had a massive impact on how 1948 was understood in popular and political narratives in the United States.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The 1948 Palestine war is also sometimes referred to as the 1948 Arab–Israeli war, the First Arab–Israeli war, or simply the 1948 war, although the term "Arab-Israeli war" often refers to the international phase of the war between Arab countries and Israel after May 15, 1948.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Palestinians and the Arab world often refer to the war as the Nakba ("the catastrophe"), while in Israel the conflict is known as the War of Independence (*Milhemet Ha'atzma'ut*).
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] A 1960 movie *Exodus* starring Paul Newman as Haganah rebel Ari Ben Canaan, a decorated former captain in the Jewish Brigade of the British Army in the Second World War, obtains a cargo ship.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] He smuggles 611 Jews out of a Cyprus camp run by the British and onto the ship for an illegal voyage to Mandatory Palestine.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] An American epic historical drama film about the founding of the State of Israel.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Produced and directed by Otto Preminger, the screenplay was adapted from the 1958 novel of the same name by Leon Uris.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] A 1966 movie *Cast a Giant Shadow* starring Kirk Douglas as US Colonel Mickey Marcus (1901–1948) who commanded units of the fledgling Israel Defense Forces during the 1948 Arab-Israeli War.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] One of the well known Israeli Machal soldiers, becoming Israel's first modern general (Hebrew: Aluf).
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Judith and colleagues are smuggled into Damascus, and after days of searching, they find Schiller.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] As they are about to capture him, Judith shoots and wounds him.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] Schiller is smuggled back to Palestine and interrogated.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] A 2015 PBS documentary, *A Wing and a Prayer*, depicts the Al Schwimmer-led airborne smuggling missions to arm Israel.
[src:age-of-discovery/1948-palestine-war] The 2021 historical drama film *Farha* tells the story of a Palestinian girl during the 1948 displacement of Palestinians from their homeland.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Concentrated at Persepolis, it consisted of an elaborate set of grand festivities that sought to honour the legacy of the Achaemenid Empire, which was founded by Cyrus the Great in 550 BC.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The event was aimed at highlighting ancient Iranian history and also showcasing the country's contemporary advances under Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had been reigning as the Shah of Iran since 1941.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The site brought sixty members of royalty and heads of state from abroad.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] As a result, some accounts have overstated the event's costs and luxuries.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The planning for the party took a year, according to the 2016 BBC *Storyville* documentary *Decadence and Downfall: The Shah of Iran's Ultimate Party*.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The filmmakers interviewed people tasked by the Shah to organize the party.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Asadollah Alam, minister of the Royal Court, was named to head the organizing committee.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The Cyrus Cylinder appeared in the official logo as the symbol for the event.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] With the decision to hold the main event at the ancient city of Persepolis, near Shiraz, the local infrastructure had to be improved, including the Shiraz International Airport and a highway to Persepolis.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] While the press and supporting staff would be housed in Shiraz, the main festivities were planned for Persepolis.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] An elaborate tent city was planned to house attendees.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The area around Persepolis was cleared of snakes and other vermin.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Trees and flowers were planted, and 50,000 song birds were imported from Europe.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Other events were scheduled for Pasargadae, the site of the Tomb of Cyrus, as well as Tehran.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The Tent City (also called Golden City) was planned by the Parisian interior-design firm of Maison Jansen on 160 acres (0.65 km2).
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] They referred to the meeting between Francis I of France and Henry VIII of England at the Field of the Cloth of Gold in 1520.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Fifty 'tents' (prefabricated luxury apartments with traditional Persian tent-cloth surrounds) were arranged in a star pattern around a central fountain.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Numerous trees were planted around them in the desert, to recreate how ancient Persepolis would have looked.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Each tent was provided with direct telephone and telex connections for attendees to their respective countries.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The entire celebration was televised to the world by way of a satellite connection from the site.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The large 'Tent of Honor' was designed for the reception of the dignitaries.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The 'Banqueting Hall' was the largest structure, and measured 68 by 24 metres (223 ft × 79 ft).
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The tent site was surrounded by gardens of trees and other plants flown in from France and adjacent to the ruins of Persepolis.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Catering services were provided by Maxim's de Paris, which closed its restaurant in Paris for almost two weeks to provide for the glittering celebrations.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Legendary hotelier Max Blouet came out of retirement to supervise the banquet.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Lanvin designed the uniforms of the Imperial Household.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] 250 red Mercedes-Benz 600 limousines were used to chauffeur guests from the airport and back.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The dinnerware was created using Limoges porcelain and linen by D.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The festivities were opened on 12 October 1971, when the Shah and the Shahbanu paid homage to Cyrus the Great at his mausoleum at Pasargadae.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] For the next two days, the Shah and his wife greeted arriving guests, often directly at Shiraz's airport.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] On 14 October, a grand gala dinner took place in the Banqueting Hall in celebration of the birthday of the Shahbanu.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Sixty members of royal families and heads of state were assembled at the single large serpentine table in the Banqueting Hall.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] They dined off a special dinner service of 10,000 plates commissioned from the English china manufacturer Spode, each plate decorated in turquoise and gold, with the Shah's coat of arms.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The official toast was raised with a Dom Perignon Rosé 1959.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Six hundred guests dined over five and a half hours, thus making for the longest and most lavish official banquet in modern history as recorded in successive editions of the *Guinness Book of World Records*.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] A son et lumière show, the *Polytope of Persepolis* designed by Iannis Xenakis and accompanied by the specially-commissioned electronic music piece *Persepolis*, concluded the evening.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] In the evening, a less formal "traditional Persian party" was held in the Banqueting Hall as the concluding event at Persepolis.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] On the final day, the Shah inaugurated the Shahyad Tower (later renamed the Azadi Tower after the Iranian Revolution) in Tehran to commemorate the event.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The tower was also home to the Museum of Persian History.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] In it was displayed the Cyrus Cylinder, which the Shah promoted as "the first human rights charter in history".
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The cylinder was also the official symbol of the celebrations, and the Shah's first speech at Cyrus' tomb praised the freedom that it had proclaimed, two and a half millennia previously.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The festivities were concluded with the Shah paying homage to his father, Reza Shah Pahlavi, at his mausoleum.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The event brought together the rulers of two of the three oldest extant monarchies, the Shah and Emperor Haile Selassie I of Ethiopia.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Emperor Hirohito of Japan was represented by his youngest brother, Prince Mikasa.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] By the end of the decade, both the Ethiopian and Iranian monarchies had ceased to exist.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Persepolis was a favoured site for the festivities as it was isolated and thus could be tightly guarded, a very important consideration when many of the world's leaders were gathered there.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Iran's security services, SAVAK, captured and took into "preventive custody" anyone that it suspected of being a potential threat.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The Ministry of the Court placed the cost at US$17 million (at that time); Ansari, one of the organizers, puts it at US$22 million (at that time).
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The actual figure is difficult to calculate exactly and is a partisan issue.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] *The New York Times* reported several months before the event, "The enormous expense of the celebration is hardly likely to strain the treasury, which is enriched by oil and many other resources.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] According to the BBC documentary *Decadence and Downfall*, the celebrations cost about 120 million United States dollars.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] However, this claim has been described as having no real basis.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] In addition, the documentary claims the approximately 50,000 birds the Shah imported died within a few days due to the desert climate.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Historian Robert Steele has described this claim as infeasible, arguing that the October climate in Persepolis is more mild than reported and so the birds would have been accustomed to the local weather.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Many accounts from journalists and historians exaggerate cost estimates and claim the regime wanted to spend whatever was necessary.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] However, the Shah only approved the celebration plans after the scope was reduced to one-quarter of the original plan in order to reduce costs.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Queen Elizabeth II had been advised not to attend, with security being an issue.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The Duke of Edinburgh and Princess Anne represented her instead.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Other major leaders who did not attend were Richard Nixon and Georges Pompidou.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Nixon had initially planned to attend but later changed his mind and sent Spiro Agnew instead.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Some materials say that the attendee on China’s behalf was Guo Moruo.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] According to his daughter, Guo was originally planned to attend, but he fell ill in transit and then-Chinese Ambassador to Pakistan Zhang Tong attended instead.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Iran's National Film Board produced a documentary of the celebrations, titled *Forugh-e Javidan* (فروغ جاویدان, lit.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] 'Eternal Light') in Persian and *Flames of Persia* in English.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The film was aimed at a Western audience.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Despite a requirement to show the film in 60 cinemas in Tehran, its "overheated rhetoric" and popular resentment at the extravagance of the event meant it did poorly at the domestic box office.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] In the *Review of Middle East Studies* in 1980, Ellen-Fairbanks Bodman referred to "a Cecil B.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Only two chadors are in fleeting evidence among the crowds, and the camera prefers girls dancing in tight corduroy pants.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Persepolis remains a major tourist attraction in Iran.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] In 2005, reports suggested that the Islamic Republic of Iran intended to reconstruct the tent city created for the 1971 celebration.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] In 2005, it was visited by nearly 35,000 people during the Nowruz holiday.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The tent city continued operating for private and government rent until 1979, when it was looted in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution and the departure of the Shah.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The iron rods for the tents and roads built for the festival area still remain and are open to the public, but there are no markers indicating what they were originally for.
[src:age-of-discovery/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The dedicated Shahyad Tower remains as a major landmark in Tehran, although it was renamed Azadi Tower in 1979.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February 2022, during the Russo-Ukrainian war, Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine, starting the current phase of the war, the largest conflict in Europe since World War II.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By April 2022, the invasion's initial goal of a rapid Russian victory via decapitation had failed, with Ukraine pushing back the northern arm of the invasion and preventing the capture of Kyiv.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Following this, the war transitioned to more conventional fighting in the south and east of Ukraine.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In a televised address, Russian president Vladimir Putin announced the invasion, calling it a "special military operation".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said that its purpose was to support the Russian-backed breakaway republics of Donetsk and Luhansk, whose paramilitary forces had been fighting Ukraine in the war in Donbas since 2014.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin espoused irredentist and imperialist views challenging Ukraine's legitimacy as a state, baselessly claimed that the Ukrainian government were neo-Nazis committing genocide against the Russian minority in the Donbas, and said that Russia's goal was to "demilitarise and denazify" Ukraine.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In late 2021, Russia massed troops near Ukraine's borders and issued demands to the West including a ban on Ukraine ever joining the NATO military alliance.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After repeatedly denying having plans to attack Ukraine, on 24 February 2022, Russian air strikes and a ground invasion were launched on a northern front from Belarus towards the capital Kyiv, a southern front from Crimea, and an eastern front from the Donbas and towards Kharkiv.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine enacted martial law, ordered a general mobilisation, and severed diplomatic relations with Russia.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion was met with widespread international condemnation.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The United Nations General Assembly passed a resolution condemning the invasion and demanding a full Russian withdrawal.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Court of Justice ordered Russia to halt military operations, and the Council of Europe expelled Russia.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Many countries imposed sanctions on Russia and its ally Belarus and provided humanitarian and military aid to Ukraine.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Baltic states and Poland declared Russia a terrorist state.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests occurred around the world, with anti-war protesters in Russia being met by mass arrests and greater media censorship.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into crimes against humanity, war crimes, abduction of Ukrainian children, and genocide against Ukrainians.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The ICC issued arrest warrants for Putin and other Russian officials.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In 2013, Ukraine's parliament overwhelmingly approved finalising an association agreement with the European Union (EU), which had been negotiated for several years.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia put pressure on Ukraine to reject the agreement and imposed economic sanctions on the country.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin adviser Sergei Glazyev warned in September 2013 that if Ukraine signed the EU agreement, Russia would no longer acknowledge Ukraine's borders.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In November, Ukrainian president Viktor Yanukovych suddenly withdrew from signing the agreement, choosing closer ties to the Russian-led Eurasian Economic Union instead.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This coerced withdrawal triggered a wave of protests known as Euromaidan, culminating in the Revolution of Dignity in February 2014.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Despite signing an agreement, Yanukovych fled.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Parliament voted to remove him and he ended up in Russia.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian soldiers with no insignia occupied the Ukrainian territory of Crimea, and seized the Crimean Parliament.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia annexed Crimea in March 2014, after a widely disputed referendum held under occupation.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Pro-Russian protests immediately followed in the Ukrainian cities of Donetsk and Luhansk.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war in Donbas began in April 2014 when armed Russian mercenaries led by Igor 'Strelkov' Girkin seized Sloviansk and nearby towns.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops were covertly involved in the fighting.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Minsk agreements, signed in September 2014 and February 2015, aimed to resolve the conflict, but ceasefires and further negotiations repeatedly failed.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] There was a large Russian military build-up near Ukraine's borders in March and April 2021, and again in both Russia and Belarus from October 2021 onward.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Members of the Russian government, including Putin, denied having plans to attack or invade Ukraine up until the day before the invasion.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] While Russian troops massed on Ukraine's borders, Russia's proxy forces launched thousands of attacks on Ukrainian forces in the Donbas.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Observers from the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE), which also includes Ukraine and Russia, reported more than 90,000 ceasefire violations throughout 2021; the vast majority in Russian-controlled territory.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In July 2021, Putin published an essay "On the Historical Unity of Russians and Ukrainians", in which he called Ukraine "historically Russian lands" and claimed there is "no historical basis" for the "idea of Ukrainian people as a nation separate from the Russians".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin was accused of promoting Russian imperialism, historical revisionism and disinformation.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024, Michael McFaul and Robert Person described this essay as representing not only "cynical propaganda" but also Putin's "deeply held and internalized beliefs".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In December 2021, Russia issued an ultimatum to the West, which included demands that NATO end all activity in its Eastern European member states and ban Ukraine or any other former Soviet state from ever joining the alliance.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia's government said NATO was a threat and warned of a military response if it followed an "aggressive line".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg replied that "Russia has no veto" on whether Ukraine joins, and "has no right to establish a sphere of influence to try to control their neighbours".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Several Western political analysts suggested Russia knew that its "unrealistic demands" would be rejected, which would give it a pretext to invade.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political scientists Michael McFaul and Robert Person said Russia's occupation of Crimea and the Donbas since 2014 had already blocked Ukraine's NATO membership, suggesting that Putin's real aim was to subjugate Ukraine.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO offered to negotiate some of Russia's demands and to improve military transparency, as long as Russia stopped its troop buildup.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The alliance rejected Russia's demand to keep Ukraine out of NATO forever, pointing out that Russia had signed agreements affirming the right of Ukraine and other countries to join alliances.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The US proposed that itself and Russia sign an agreement not to station missiles or troops in Ukraine.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin replied that Russia's demands had been "ignored", and the Russian troop buildup continued.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Western leaders vowed that heavy sanctions would be imposed should Putin choose to invade rather than to negotiate.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] French president Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz met Putin in February 2022 to dissuade him from invading.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Scholz, Putin told him that Ukraine should not be an independent state.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Scholz told Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelenskyy to declare Ukraine a neutral country and renounce its aspirations to join NATO.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said Putin had broken agreements and could not be trusted to respect Ukrainian neutrality.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine had been a neutral country in 2014 when Russia occupied Crimea and invaded the Donbas.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 19 February, Zelenskyy made a speech at the Munich Security Conference, calling for Western powers to end their "appeasement" of Putin and give a timeframe for when Ukraine could join NATO.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political analysts Taras Kuzio and Vladimir Socor agree that "when Russia made its decision to invade Ukraine, that country was more remote than ever not only from NATO membership but from any track that might lead to membership".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting in Donbas escalated from 17 February 2022.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainians and the Russian separatists accused one another of firing into their respective territories.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 February, the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics ordered all civilians to leave their capitals, although observers noted that full evacuations would take months.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian media reported a sharp increase in artillery shelling by the Russian-led militants in Donbas as an attempt to provoke the Ukrainian army.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Separatist leaders warned that Ukraine was about to launch an offensive, but they gave no evidence, and *The Guardian* noted it would be "exceedingly risky" for Ukraine to assault the Donbas while Russian troops were massed on its borders.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said his military would not respond to the provocations.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the days leading up to the invasion, the Russian government intensified its disinformation campaign.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine and Western leaders accused Russia of staging false flag attacks to give Russia a pretext for invading.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian state media aired fabricated videos that purported to show Ukrainian forces attacking Russians in Donbas; evidence showed that the claimed attacks, explosions, and evacuations were staged by Russia.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 17 February, Russian proxy forces shelled a kindergarten and blamed it on Ukraine, although the kindetgarten was in Ukrainian-held territory.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, the head of the Russian Federal Security Service (FSB) said that Russian forces had killed five Ukrainian "saboteurs" that crossed into Russian territory, capturing one Ukrainian serviceman and destroying two armoured vehicles.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The claim was denied by Ukraine and drew warnings that Russia was seeking further justification to start an invasion.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, Putin announced that the Russian government would recognise the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, Putin directed that Russian troops be deployed to the Donbas, in what he called a "peacekeeping mission".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the same speech, Putin questioned the validity of the Ukrainian nation, stating that "Modern Ukraine was entirely created by Russia", views which Michael McFaul and Robert Person, writing in 2024, described as "grotesque".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The 21 February intervention in Donbas was condemned by several members of the UN Security Council; none voiced support.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 22 February, video footage shot in the early morning showed Russian armed forces and tanks moving in the Donbas region.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Federation Council unanimously authorised the use of military force outside Russia.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Zelenskyy ordered the conscription of army reservists.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The following day, Ukraine's parliament proclaimed a 30-day nationwide state of emergency and ordered the mobilisation of all reservists.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia began to evacuate its embassy in Kyiv.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The websites of the Ukrainian parliament and government, along with banking websites, were hit by DDoS attacks, widely attributed to Russian-backed hackers.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the night of 23 February, Zelenskyy gave a speech in Russian in which he appealed to the citizens of Russia to prevent war.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He also refuted Russia's claims about the presence of neo-Nazis in the Ukrainian government and said that he had no intention of attacking the Donbas region.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov said on 23 February that the separatist leaders in Donetsk and Luhansk had sent a letter to Putin stating that Ukrainian shelling had caused civilian deaths and appealing for Russian military support.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Ukraine requested an urgent UN Security Council meeting.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Half an hour into the emergency meeting, Putin announced the start of military operations in Ukraine.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sergiy Kyslytsya, the Ukrainian representative, subsequently called on the Russian representative, Vasily Nebenzya, to "do everything possible to stop the war" or relinquish his position as president of the UN Security Council; Nebenzya refused.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The decision to invade was reportedly made by Putin and a small group of war hawks or *siloviki* in Putin's inner circle, including national security adviser Nikolai Patrushev and defence minister Sergei Shoigu.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the start of the invasion, Ukrainian and Western analysts assessed that Putin seemed to have believed that the Russian Armed Forces would be capable of seizing Kyiv within days.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This assessment led to the conclusion that "taking Kyiv in three days" had been the original goal of the invasion.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The narrative of the planned "three day" capture of Kyiv was reinforced by statements by Aleksandr Lukashenko and Margarita Simonyan, editor-in-chief of Russian state-controlled broadcaster RT.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, the Security Service of Ukraine (SBU) repeated the claim following its release of a video showing a captured Russian soldier claiming that his unit was sent into Ukraine with food supplies for only three days.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Documents found inside Russian tanks mention how the "special military operation" would conclude in ten days.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine also captured "flagship" tanks – as used in parades – along with military parade uniforms, suggesting that Russia expected to stage a victory parade in Kyiv after a swift conquest.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin himself asserted back in 2014 that Russian forces "could take Ukraine in two weeks".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three days after the invasion began, RIA Novosti, a Russian state news agency, mistakenly published an article called "Russia's Coming and the New World", which had been made in advance in anticipation of a Russian victory; it announced that "Ukraine had returned to Russia".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy also said that Russia had sent him an ultimatum to step down and be replaced with Viktor Medvedchuk.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time on 24 February, Putin, in another speech, announced a "special military operation", which effectively declared war on Ukraine.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said the operation was to "protect the people" of the Russian-controlled breakaway republics.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said Russia sought the "demilitarisation and denazification" of Ukraine, and denied the legitimacy of the Ukrainian state.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said he had no plans to occupy Ukraine.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began within minutes of Putin's speech.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In order to justify the invasion of Ukraine within the context of international norms, Putin cited the 1999 NATO bombing of Yugoslavia and 2003 US invasion of Iraq.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion comprised nearly 150,000 troops, organised in about 140 Battalion Tactical Groups.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The forces of the Russia-controlled LNR and DNR, and paramilitary forces engaged in the invasion, raised total Russian-controlled forces employed in the campaign to as many as 200,000.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These forces were organised into groups having tactical signs to distinguish them, and were to advance into Ukraine along at least ten different axes of advance.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Rather than having a unified command-structure, these groups were organised under different Russian military-district command-posts named after the region of Russia in which their respective military-district was located.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three groups, all having the tactical sign "Z" and commanded by the Western Military District under Alexander Zhuravlyov, were to advance into Ukraine respectively from Kursk, Belgorod and Voronezh.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Groups under the Southern Military District under Aleksandr Dvornikov were identified with a "Z in a square" tactical symbol, and, advancing from occupied Crimea, were tasked with surrounding Mariupol, capturing Zaporizhia, seizing Kherson, and crossing the Dnieper river to take Voznesensk.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion were equipped with roughly 2,800 tanks ready for combat, with another 400 approximately in the hands of the Russian-controlled proxy forces of the LNR and DNR.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces at the outbreak of the war comprised roughly 20 combat-ready brigades, of which more than half were located in the east of the country, positioned along the line of contact in the "Joint Forces Operation" zone in Donbas.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] An additional manoeuvre brigade and two brigades of artillery were located in the Kyiv region, with other forces also deployed in the area of Kharkiv, Dnipro, Sumy, and Odesa.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] No major combat units were located on the Gomel or Crimean axes.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian tank-forces had roughly 900 battle-ready tanks organised in some 30 battalions at the time of the invasion.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of these tank battalions were formed in the period 2014–2018, when roughly 500 tanks were delivered to the Ukrainian armed forces, mostly reconditioned older tanks rather than new-built tanks, particularly T-64B and T-64-BM tanks.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The tank battalions were spread between Ukraine's two regular and four reserve armoured brigades, as well as tank units attached to brigades of mechanised, mountain, airborne and marine infantry.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In contrast to the direct-fire techniques practised in most armoured forces, Ukrainian forces had, based on their experience during the war in Donbas, developed a technique of using tanks in the indirect-fire role.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This meant Ukrainian tank forces acting essentially as mobile artillery that did not require the kind of screening that traditional artillery units require.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began at dawn on 24 February.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting began in Luhansk Oblast at 3:40 a.m.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time near Milove on the border with Russia.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The main infantry and tank attacks were launched in four spearheads, creating a northern front launched towards Kyiv from Belarus, a southern front from Crimea, a southeastern front from Russian-controlled Donbas, and an eastern front from Russia towards Kharkiv and Sumy.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian vehicles were subsequently marked with a white *Z* military symbol (a non-Cyrillic letter), believed to be a measure to prevent friendly fire.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Immediately after the invasion began, Zelenskyy declared martial law in Ukraine in a first video speech.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, he ordered a general mobilisation of all Ukrainian males between 18 and 60 years old, prohibiting them from leaving the country.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wagner Group mercenaries and Kadyrovites contracted by the Kremlin reportedly made several attempts to assassinate Zelenskyy, including an operation involving several hundred mercenaries meant to infiltrate Kyiv with the aim of killing the Ukrainian president.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainian government said anti-war officials within Russia's FSB shared the plans with them.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy appeared defiant in video messages on 24 through 26 February, that he and his cabinet is still in Kyiv.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February NATO met and its countries pledged military aid for Ukraine and on 27 February Germany called the invasion a historic watershed.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] That day in the evening Putin put Russia's nuclear deterrence into alert.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian invasion was unexpectedly met by fierce Ukrainian resistance.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Kyiv, Russia failed to take the city and was repulsed in the battles of Irpin, Hostomel, and Bucha.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians tried to encircle the capital, but its defenders under Oleksandr Syrskyi held their ground, effectively using Western Javelin anti-tank missiles and Stinger anti-aircraft missiles to thin Russian supply lines and stall the offensive.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the southern front, Russian forces had captured the regional capital of Kherson by 2 March.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A column of Russian tanks and armoured vehicles was ambushed on 9 March outside of Brovary and sustained heavy losses that forced them to retreat.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian army adopted siege tactics on the western front around the key cities of Chernihiv, Sumy and Kharkiv, but failed to capture them due to stiff resistance and logistical setbacks.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Mykolaiv Oblast, Russian forces advanced as far as Voznesensk, but were repelled and pushed back south of Mykolaiv.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A second axis, deployed towards eastern Kyiv from Russia by the Central Military District (northeastern front), comprised the 41st Combined Arms Army and the 2nd Guards Combined Arms Army.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third axis was deployed towards Kharkiv by the Western Military District (eastern front), with the 1st Guards Tank Army and 20th Combined Arms Army.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 7 April, Russian troops deployed to the northern front by the Russian Eastern Military District pulled back from the Kyiv offensive, reportedly to resupply and redeploy to the Donbas region in an effort to reinforce the renewed invasion of southeastern Ukraine.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The northeastern front, including the Central Military District, was similarly withdrawn for resupply and redeployment to southeastern Ukraine.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian efforts to capture Kyiv included a probative spearhead on 24 February, from Belarus south along the west bank of the Dnipro River.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The apparent intent was to encircle the city from the west, supported by two separate axes of attack from Russia along the east bank of the Dnipro: the western at Chernihiv, and from the east at Sumy.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These were likely intended to encircle Kyiv from the northeast and east.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia tried to seize Kyiv quickly, with Spetsnaz infiltrating into the city supported by airborne operations and a rapid mechanised advance from the north, but failed.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reporter Glenn Kessler said it came from "a single source, but on the surface it appears to be a good one".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advancing on Kyiv from Belarus gained control of the ghost town of Chernobyl.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian Airborne Forces attempted to seize two key airfields near Kyiv, launching an airborne assault on Antonov Airport, and a similar landing at Vasylkiv, near Vasylkiv Air Base, on 26 February.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By early March, further Russian advances along the west side of the Dnipro were limited, after suffering setbacks from Ukrainian defence.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As of 5 March, a large Russian convoy, reportedly 64 kilometres (40 mi) in length, had made little progress toward Kyiv.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The London-based think tank Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) assessed the Russian performance from the north and east as "stalled".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Advances along the Chernihiv axis had largely halted as a siege of the city began.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also continued advancing from the northwest of Kyiv, capturing Bucha, Hostomel, and Vorzel by 5 March, though Irpin remained contested as of 9 March.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 11 March, it was reported that the lengthy convoy had largely dispersed, taking up positions that offered tree cover.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 16 March, Ukrainian forces began a counter-offensive to repel Russian forces approaching Kyiv from several surrounding cities.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 20 March, the Russian military appeared to be waging a rapid invasion to achieve its apparent primary goal of the seizure of Kyiv, along with the occupation of Eastern Ukraine and the overthrow of the Ukrainian government.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Unable to achieve a quick victory in Kyiv, Russian forces switched strategies and began using standoff weapons, indiscriminate bombing, and siege warfare.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Ukrainian counteroffensive in Kyiv resulted in several towns, including Makariv, being retaken to the east and west of Kyiv.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As part of a general retreat of Russian forces north of Kyiv, as well as attacks on Russian formations by the Ukrainian military, Russian troops in the Bucha area retreated north by the end of March.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces entered the city on 1 April.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine claimed to recapture the entire region around Kyiv, including Irpin, Bucha, and Hostomel, by 2 April, with evidence of war crimes being uncovered in Bucha.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advanced into Chernihiv Oblast on 24 February, besieging its administrative capital within four days of fighting.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February Ukrainian forces lost control over Konotop.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also attacked Okhtyrka, deploying thermobaric weapons.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 4 March, Frederick Kagan wrote that the Sumy axis was then "the most successful and dangerous Russian avenue of advance on Kyiv", and commented that the geography favoured mechanised advances as the terrain "is flat and sparsely populated, offering few good defensive positions".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Travelling along highways, Russian forces reached Brovary, an eastern suburb of Kyiv, on 4 March.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Pentagon confirmed on 6 April that the Russian army had left Chernihiv Oblast, but Sumy Oblast remained contested.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 7 April, the governor of Sumy Oblast said that Russian troops were gone, but had left behind rigged explosives and other hazards.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces took control of the North Crimean Canal, allowing Crimea to obtain water from the Dnieper, which had been cut off since 2014.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February, the siege of Mariupol began as the attack moved east linking to separatist-held Donbas.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] En route, Russian forces entered Berdiansk and captured it.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, Russian units from the DPR were fighting near Pavlopil as they moved on Mariupol.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By evening, the Russian Navy began an amphibious assault on the coast of the Sea of Azov 70 kilometres (43 mi) west of Mariupol.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A US defence official said that Russian forces were deploying thousands of marines from this beachhead.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian 22nd Army Corps approached the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant on 26 February and besieged Enerhodar.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A fire began, but the Ukrainian military said that essential equipment was undamaged.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third Russian attack group from Crimea moved northwest and captured the bridge over the Dnieper.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian troops took Kherson; this was the first major city to fall to Russian forces.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops moved on Mykolaiv and attacked it two days later.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After renewed missile attacks on 14 March in Mariupol, the Ukrainian government said more than 2,500 had died.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 18 March, Mariupol was completely encircled and fighting reached the city centre, hampering efforts to evacuate civilians.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 20 March, an art school sheltering around 400 people, was destroyed by Russian bombs.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians demanded surrender, and the Ukrainians refused.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin told Emmanuel Macron in a phone call on 29 March that the bombardment of Mariupol would only end when the Ukrainians surrendered.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 April, Russian troops refused safe passage into Mariupol to 50 buses sent by the United Nations to evacuate civilians, as peace talks continued in Istanbul.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 3 April, following the retreat of Russian forces from Kyiv, Russia expanded its attack on southern Ukraine further west, with bombardment and strikes against Odesa, Mykolaiv, and the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the east, Russian troops attempted to capture Kharkiv, less than 35 kilometres (22 mi) from the Russian border, and met strong Ukrainian resistance.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces with OTR-21 Tochka missiles, which according to Ukrainian officials, destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and started a fire.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 March, Denis Pushilin, head of the DPR, announced that DPR forces had almost completely surrounded the city of Volnovakha.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian forces were repelled from Sievierodonetsk during an attack against the city.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the same day, Ukrainian forces initiated a counter-offensive on Horlivka, controlled by the DPR.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Izium was captured by Russian forces on 1 April after a monthlong battle.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Russian defence ministry said it would seek to occupy major cities in eastern Ukraine.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 31 March, *PBS News* reported renewed shelling and missile attacks in Kharkiv, as bad or worse than before, as peace talks with Russia were to resume in Istanbul.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Amid the heightened Russian shelling of Kharkiv on 31 March, Russia reported a helicopter strike against an oil supply depot approximately 35 kilometres (22 mi) north of the border in Belgorod, and accused Ukraine of the attack.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Local governor Maksym Kozytskyy reported that at least 35 people had been killed in the attacks.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 March, Russia expanded the attack to Lviv, with Ukrainian military officials saying initial information suggested that the missiles which hit Lviv were likely air-launched cruise missiles originating from warplanes flying over the Black Sea.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces attacked the Chuhuiv air base, which housed Bayraktar TB2 drones.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The attack caused damage to fuel storage areas and infrastructure.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The next day, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces using OTR-21 Tochka missiles.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Ukrainian officials, this destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and set the airbase on fire.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the Zhytomyr Airport attack on 27 February, it was reported that Russia used 9K720 Iskander missile systems, located in Belarus, to attack the civilian Zhytomyr Airport.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia lost at least ten aircraft on 5 March.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 6 March, the General Staff of the Armed Forces of Ukraine reported that 88 Russian aircraft had been destroyed since the war began.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, an anonymous senior US defence official told Reuters on 7 March that Russia still had the "vast majority" of its fighter jets and helicopters that had been amassed near Ukraine available to fly.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the first month of the invasion, Justin Bronk, a British military observer, counted the Russian aircraft losses at 15 fixed-wing aircraft and 35 helicopters, but noted that the true total was certainly higher.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 13 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine lies on the Black Sea, which only has access through the Turkish-held Bosphorus and Dardanelles straits.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 28 February, Turkey invoked the 1936 Montreux Convention and sealed off the straits to Russian warships not registered as having Black Sea home bases and not returning to their ports of origin.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This prevented the passage of four Russian naval vessels through the Turkish Straits.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, the State Border Guard Service of Ukraine announced that an attack on Snake Island by Russian Navy ships had begun.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The cruiser *Moskva* and patrol boat *Vasily Bykov* bombarded the island with their deck guns.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] When the Russian warship identified itself and instructed the Ukrainian soldiers stationed on the island to surrender, their response was "Russian warship, go fuck yourself!" After the bombardment, a detachment of Russian soldiers landed and took control of Snake Island.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia stated on 26 February that US drones were supplying intelligence to the Ukrainian navy to help target Russian warships in the Black Sea, which the US denied.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 3 March, the Ukrainian frigate *Hetman Sahaidachny*, the flagship of the Ukrainian navy, was scuttled in Mykolaiv to prevent its capture by Russian forces.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, the Russian source RT reported that the Russian Armed Forces had captured about a dozen Ukrainian ships in Berdiansk, including the *Polnocny*-class landing ship *Yuri Olefirenko*.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 March, Ukrainian officials said that a Russian landing ship docked in Berdiansk was destroyed by a Ukrainian rocket attack.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Military analysts have been highly critical of the Russian plan of invasion.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kofman also criticised the use of "thunder runs" similar to those used by US forces in the 2003 Iraq war, in an environment where resistance to such attempts to go around urban centres was likely to be far higher.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The November 2022 Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) report on the invasion also criticised the invasion plan as being based on "false assumptions", and spreading Russian forces too thinly across too many objectives, with insufficient contingency-planning for what to do if things went wrong.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Nevertheless, RUSI also stated that "If competently executed, these plans could have succeeded".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024 in the *Journal of Strategic Studies*, analysts from the Swiss Military Academy at ETH Zurich characterised the invasion plan as being "predicated on a rapid, decisive overthrow of the government in Kyiv, presuming minimal resistance".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] They also criticised what they saw as the excessively rigid, Soviet-style command structure and operational planning of Russian forces during the invasion.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian air forces during the campaign were described by military analyst Sean M.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser, writing in 2023 in the *Small Wars & Insurgencies* journal, as having "bungled air operations from the outset of the war".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser described the Russian air forces as having "settled largely for a 'tie'" during the period of the invasion.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The force-structure of Russian forces during the invasion has also been criticised, particularly the use of battalion tactical groups (BTGs), which proved brittle once Ukrainian resistance was met.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Whilst praising Ukraine's resistance to the invasion, analysts have also identified deficiencies in the deployment of Ukrainian forces before the invasion.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] At the tactical level, however, RUSI assessed Ukrainian forces as comprising "units which had been psychologically and practically preparing for this fight for eight years".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Alexander Hill described Ukrainian forces as having undergone a transformation since the fighting of 2014, and having become "a stubborn opponent that was typically difficult [for Russian troops] to dislodge".
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces did not deploy an overall commander for the invasion of Ukraine, with command divided between the military district commanders, each of whom was assigned to their own axis of attack.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Mason Clark of the Institute for the Study of War, this resulted in commanders competing for central resources and each effectively fighting their own war.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Subsequent to the failure of this strategy, according to Clark, Putin appointed Aleksandr Dvornikov as an overall commander in Ukraine on 8 April 2022, however Dvornikov retained his post as commander of the Southern Military District.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Disatisfied with Dvornikov's performance, according to Clark, Putin then dismissed Dvornikov as overall commander in June 2022 but allowed him to remain in overall command for several weeks, before Gennady Zhidko was reportedly appointed to that role.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, according to Clark, both Zhidko and Dvornikov were effectively "first among equals" among the Russian Military District Commanders rather than true theatre commanders, and it was not until October 2022 that a dedicated theatre commander - Sergey Surovikin - was appointed.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia abandoned the attempt to take Kyiv in early April, but a lasting state of war between Russia and Ukraine remained, with Russia capturing Mariupol by 20 May 2022, and maintaining an occupation of large portions of four Ukrainian oblasts—Donetsk, Kherson, Luhansk, and Zaporizhzhia.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In August, Ukrainian forces began liberating territories in the north-east and south.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 30 September 2022, Russia declared the annexation of the four partially-occupied oblasts, which was internationally condemned.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of Luhansk Oblast and part of Donetsk Oblast had been controlled by pro-Russian separatists since 2014, while the Kherson and Zaporizhzhia oblasts were invaded by Russia in 2022.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The boundaries of the areas to be annexed and their borders were not defined; Russian officials stated that they would be defined later.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] None of the oblasts were fully under Russian control at the time of the declaration, nor since.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] If limited to the areas then under Russian control (about 90,000 km2 or 15% of Ukraine's territory, roughly the size of Portugal) the annexation would still be the largest in Europe since World War II.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In other respects as well—in terms of the scale and intensity of hostilities, and the number of casualties—after the invasion, the war became the biggest war in Europe since World War II.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] From then through 2023, Russian offensives and Ukrainian counteroffensives gained only small amounts of territory.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war has also led to attacks in Russia by Ukrainian and Ukrainian-backed forces, among them a cross-border offensive into Russia's Kursk region in August 2024.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia has repeatedly carried out deliberate and indiscriminate attacks on civilians far from the frontline.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into war crimes and issued arrest warrants for Putin and several other Russian officials.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion received widespread international condemnation from governments and intergovernmental organisations.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March 2022 and on 23 February 2023, 141 member states of the UN General Assembly voted for a resolution saying that Russia should immediately withdraw.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Seven, including Russia, voted against the measure.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political reactions to the invasion included new sanctions imposed on Russia, which triggered widespread economic effects on the Russian and world economies.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sanctions forced Russia to reorient its oil exports to non-sanctioning countries such as India, rely more on LNG (which was not subject to European Union sanctions), and shift its coal exports from Europe to Asia.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most European countries cancelled nuclear cooperation with Russia.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Over seventy sovereign states and the European Union delivered humanitarian aid to Ukraine, and nearly fifty countries plus the EU provided military aid.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Economic sanctions included a ban on Russian aircraft using EU airspace, a ban of certain Russian banks from the SWIFT international payments system, and a ban on certain Russian media outlets.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reactions to the invasion have included public response, media responses, peace efforts, and the examination of the legal implications of the invasion.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Some countries, particularly in the Global South, saw public sympathy or outright support for Russia, due in part to distrust of US foreign policy.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests and demonstrations were held worldwide, including some in Russia and parts of Ukraine occupied by Russia.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Calls for a boycott of Russian goods spread on social media platforms, while hackers attacked Russian websites, particularly those operated by the Russian government.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Anti-Russian sentiment against Russians living abroad surged after the invasion.
[src:age-of-discovery/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In March 2022, Russian's parliament introduced prison sentences of up to 15 years for publishing "fake news" about Russian military operations, intended to suppress any criticism related to the war.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Initially influenced by Toulouse-Lautrec, Gauguin, and other late-19th-century innovators, Pablo Picasso made his first cubist paintings based on Cézanne's idea that all depiction of nature can be reduced to three solids: cube, sphere, and cone.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] With the painting *Les Demoiselles d'Avignon* (1907; see gallery) Picasso created a new and radical picture depicting a raw and primitive brothel scene with five prostitutes, violently painted women, reminiscent of African tribal masks and his own new proto-Cubist inventions.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Analytic cubism, exemplified by *Violin and Candlestick, Paris*, was jointly developed by Pablo Picasso and Georges Braque from about 1908 through 1912.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Analytic cubism was followed by Synthetic cubism, characterized by the introduction of different textures, surfaces, collage elements, papier collé and a large variety of merged subject matter.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the years between 1910 and the end of World War I and after the heyday of cubism, several movements emerged in Paris.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Giorgio de Chirico moved to Paris in July 1911, where he joined his brother Andrea (the poet and painter known as Alberto Savinio).
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Through his brother he met Pierre Laprade, a member of the jury at the Salon d'Automne, where he exhibited three of his dreamlike works: *Enigma of the Oracle*, *Enigma of an Afternoon* and *Self-Portrait*.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During 1913 he exhibited his work at the Salon des Indépendants and Salon d’Automne, where his work was noticed by Pablo Picasso, Guillaume Apollinaire, and others.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His compelling and mysterious paintings are considered instrumental to the early beginnings of Surrealism.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] *Song of Love* (1914) is one of the most famous works by de Chirico and is an early example of the surrealist style, though it was painted ten years before the movement was "founded" by André Breton in 1924.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Modern painting influenced all the visual arts, from Modernist architecture and design, to avant-garde film, theatre and modern dance, and became an experimental laboratory for the expression of visual experience, from photography and concrete poetry to advertising art and fashion.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Van Gogh's paintings exerted great influence upon 20th-century Expressionism, as can be seen in the work of the Fauves, Die Brücke (a group led by German painter Ernst Kirchner), and the Expressionism of Edvard Munch, Egon Schiele, Marc Chagall, Amedeo Modigliani, Chaïm Soutine, and others.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Wassily Kandinsky, a Russian painter, printmaker and art theorist, is generally considered the first important painter of modern abstract art.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As an early modernist, in search of new modes of visual expression, and spiritual expression, he theorized—as did contemporary occultists and theosophists—that pure visual abstraction had corollary vibrations with sound and music.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] They posited that pure abstraction could express pure spirituality.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His earliest abstractions were generally titled (as the example in the above gallery) *Composition VII*, making connection to the work of the composers of music.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Kandinsky included many of his theories about abstract art in his book *Concerning the Spiritual in Art*.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Piet Mondrian's art was also related to his spiritual and philosophical studies.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1908 he became interested in the theosophical movement launched by Helena Petrovna Blavatsky in the late 19th century.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Blavatsky believed that it was possible to attain a knowledge of nature more profound than that provided by empirical means, and much of Mondrian's work for the rest of his life was inspired by his search for that spiritual knowledge.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Other major pioneers of early abstraction include Swedish painter Hilma af Klint, Russian painter Kazimir Malevich, and Swiss painter Paul Klee.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Robert Delaunay was a French artist who is associated with Orphism, (reminiscent of a link between pure abstraction and cubism).
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His later works were more abstract, reminiscent of Paul Klee.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His key contributions to abstract painting refer to his bold use of color, and a clear love of experimentation of both depth and tone.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] At the invitation of Kandinsky, Delaunay and his wife the artist Sonia Delaunay, joined The Blue Rider (Der Blaue Reiter), a Munich-based group of abstract artists, in 1911, and his art took a turn to the abstract.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Still other important pioneers of abstract painting include Czech painter, František Kupka as well as American artists Stanton Macdonald-Wright and Morgan Russell who, in 1912, founded Synchromism, an art movement that closely resembles Orphism.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Les Fauves (French for *The Wild Beasts*) were early-20th-century painters, experimenting with freedom of expression through color.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The name was given, humorously and not as a compliment, to the group by art critic Louis Vauxcelles.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvism was a short-lived and loose grouping of artists whose works emphasized painterly qualities and the imaginative use of deep color over the representational values.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvists made the subject of the painting easy to read and exaggerated perspectives.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The leaders of the movement were Henri Matisse and André Derain—friendly rivals of a sort, each with his own followers.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Ultimately Matisse became the *yang* to Picasso's *yin* in the 20th century.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvist painters included Albert Marquet, Charles Camoin, Maurice de Vlaminck, Raoul Dufy, Othon Friesz, the Dutch painter Kees van Dongen, and Picasso's partner in Cubism, Georges Braque amongst others.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvism, as a movement, had no concrete theories, and was short lived, beginning in 1905 and ending in 1907.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Matisse was seen as the leader of the movement, due to his seniority in age and prior self-establishment in the academic art world.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Matisse, *The Green Line* (above), caused a sensation in Paris when it was first exhibited.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He said he wanted to create art to delight; art as a decoration was his purpose and it can be said that his use of bright colors tries to maintain serenity of composition.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1906 at the suggestion of his dealer Ambroise Vollard, André Derain went to London and produced a series of paintings like *Charing Cross Bridge, London* (above) in the Fauvist style, paraphrasing the famous series by the Impressionist painter Claude Monet.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] By 1907 Fauvism no longer was a shocking new movement, soon it was replaced by Cubism on the critics radar screen as the latest new development in Contemporary Art of the time.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Der Blaue Reiter was a German movement lasting from 1911 to 1914, fundamental to Expressionism, along with Die Brücke, a group of German expressionist artists formed in Dresden in 1905.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Founding members of Die Brücke were Fritz Bleyl, Erich Heckel, Ernst Ludwig Kirchner and Karl Schmidt-Rottluff.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Later members included Max Pechstein, Otto Mueller and others.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] This was a seminal group, which in due course had a major impact on the evolution of modern art in the 20th century and created the style of Expressionism.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Der Blaue Reiter lacked a central artistic manifesto, but was centered around Kandinsky and Marc.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Artists Gabriele Münter and Paul Klee were also involved.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The name of the movement comes from a painting by Kandinsky created in 1903.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is also claimed that the name could have derived from Marc's enthusiasm for horses and Kandinsky's love of the colour blue.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] For Kandinsky, *blue* is the colour of spirituality: the darker the blue, the more it awakens human desire for the eternal.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Marcel Duchamp came to international prominence in the wake of the New York City Armory Show in 1913 where his *Nude Descending a Staircase* became the *cause célèbre*.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He subsequently created *The Bride Stripped Bare by Her Bachelors, Even, Large Glass*.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The *Large Glass* pushed the art of painting to radical new limits being part painting, part collage, part construction.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Duchamp (who was soon to renounce artmaking for chess) became closely associated with the Dada movement that began in neutral Zürich, Switzerland, during World War I and peaked from 1916 to 1920.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The movement primarily involved visual arts, literature (poetry, art manifestoes, art theory), theatre, and graphic design, and concentrated its anti war politic through a rejection of the prevailing standards in art through anti-art cultural works.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Francis Picabia, Man Ray, Kurt Schwitters, Tristan Tzara, Hans Richter, Jean Arp, Sophie Taeuber-Arp, along with Duchamp and many others are associated with the Dadaist movement.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Duchamp and several Dadaists are also associated with Surrealism, the movement that dominated European painting in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1924 André Breton published the *Surrealist Manifesto.* The Surrealist movement in painting became synonymous with the avant-garde and which featured artists whose works varied from the abstract to the super-realist.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] With works on paper like *Machine Turn Quickly* (above) Francis Picabia continued his involvement in the Dada movement through 1919 in Zürich and Paris, before breaking away from it after developing an interest in Surrealist art.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Yves Tanguy, René Magritte and Salvador Dalí are particularly known for their realistic depictions of dream imagery and fantastic manifestations of the imagination.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Joan Miró's *The Tilled Field* of 1923–1924 verges on abstraction, this early painting of a complex of objects and figures, and arrangements of sexually active characters; was Miró's first Surrealist masterpiece.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The more abstract Joan Miró, Jean Arp, André Masson, and Max Ernst were very influential, especially in the United States during the 1940s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Throughout the 1930s, Surrealism continued to become more visible to the public at large.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] A Surrealist group developed in Britain and, according to Breton, their 1936 London International Surrealist Exhibition was a high-water mark of the period and became the model for international exhibitions.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Surrealist groups in Japan, and especially in Latin America, the Caribbean and in Mexico produced innovative and original works.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Dalí and Magritte created some of the most widely recognized images of the movement.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The 1928/1929 painting *This Is Not A Pipe* by Magritte is the subject of a Michel Foucault 1973 book, *This is not a Pipe* (English edition, 1991), that discusses the painting and its paradox.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Dalí joined the group in 1929, and participated in the rapid establishment of the visual style between 1930 and 1935.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Evocations of time and its compelling mystery and absurdity.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Max Ernst studied philosophy and psychology in Bonn and was interested in the alternative realities experienced by the insane.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His paintings, such as *Murdering Airplane* (1920), may have been inspired by the psychoanalyst Sigmund Freud's study of the delusions of a paranoiac, Daniel Paul Schreber.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Freud identified Schreber's fantasy of becoming a woman as a *castration complex*.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The central image of two pairs of legs refers to Schreber's hermaphroditic desires.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Ernst's inscription on the back of the painting reads: *The picture is curious because of its symmetry.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1920s André Masson's work was enormously influential in helping the young artist Joan Miró find his roots in the new Surrealist painting.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Miró acknowledged in letters to his dealer Pierre Matisse the importance of Masson as an example to him in his early years in Paris.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Long after personal, political and professional tensions have fragmented the Surrealist group into thin air and ether, Magritte, Miró, Dalí and the other Surrealists continue to define a visual program in the arts.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Other prominent surrealist artists include Giorgio de Chirico, Méret Oppenheim, Toyen, Grégoire Michonze, Roberto Matta, Kay Sage, Leonora Carrington, Dorothea Tanning, and Leonor Fini among others.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1920s and the 1930s and the Great Depression, the European art scene was characterized by Surrealism, late Cubism, the Bauhaus, De Stijl, Dada, Neue Sachlichkeit, and Expressionism; and was occupied by masterful modernist color painters like Henri Matisse and Pierre Bonnard.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American Scene painting and the Social Realism and Regionalism movements that contained both political and social commentary dominated the art world in the USA.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Artists like Ben Shahn, Thomas Hart Benton, Grant Wood, George Tooker, John Steuart Curry, Reginald Marsh, and others became prominent.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Frida Kahlo's Symbolist works also relate strongly to Surrealism and to the Magic Realism movement in literature.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The psychological drama in many of Kahlo's self-portraits (above) underscore the vitality and relevance of her paintings to artists in the 21st century.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In Germany Neue Sachlichkeit ("New Objectivity") emerged as Max Beckmann, Otto Dix, George Grosz and others associated with the Berlin Secession politicized their paintings.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The work of these artists grew out of expressionism, and was a response to the political tensions of the Weimar Republic, and was often sharply satirical.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Diego Rivera is perhaps best known by the public for his 1933 mural, *Man at the Crossroads*, in the lobby of the RCA Building at Rockefeller Center.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] When his patron Nelson Rockefeller discovered that the mural included a portrait of Lenin and other communist imagery, he fired Rivera, and the unfinished work was eventually destroyed by Rockefeller's staff.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The film *Cradle Will Rock* includes a dramatization of the controversy.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Frida Kahlo (Rivera's wife's) works are often characterized by their stark portrayals of pain.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Of her 143 paintings 55 are self-portraits, which frequently incorporate symbolic portrayals of her physical and psychological wounds.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Kahlo was deeply influenced by indigenous Mexican culture, which is apparent in her paintings' bright colors and dramatic symbolism.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Christian and Jewish themes are often depicted in her work as well; she combined elements of the classic religious Mexican tradition—which were often bloody and violent—with surrealist renderings.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] While her paintings are not overtly Christian—she was an avowed communist—they certainly contain elements of the macabre Mexican Christian style of religious paintings.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1930s radical leftist politics characterized many of the artists connected to Surrealism, including Pablo Picasso.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] On 26 April 1937, during the Spanish Civil War, the Basque town of Gernika was the scene of the "Bombing of Gernika" by the Condor Legion of Nazi Germany's Luftwaffe.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The Germans were attacking to support the efforts of Francisco Franco to overthrow the Basque Government and the Spanish Republican government.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The town was devastated, though the Biscayan assembly and the Oak of Gernika survived.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Picasso painted his mural sized *Guernica* to commemorate the horrors of the bombing.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In its final form, *Guernica* is an immense black and white, 3.5 metre (11 ft) tall and 7.8 metre (23 ft) wide mural painted in oil.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The mural presents a scene of death, violence, brutality, suffering, and helplessness without portraying their immediate causes.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The choice to paint in black and white contrasts with the intensity of the scene depicted and invokes the immediacy of a newspaper photograph.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Picasso painted the mural sized painting called *Guernica* in protest of the bombing.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The painting was first exhibited in Paris in 1937, then Scandinavia, then London in 1938 and finally in 1939 at Picasso's request the painting was sent to the United States in an extended loan (for safekeeping) at MoMA.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The painting went on a tour of museums throughout the U.S. until its final return to the Museum of Modern Art in New York City where it was exhibited for nearly thirty years.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Finally in accord with Picasso's wish to give the painting to the people of Spain as a gift, it was sent to Spain in 1981.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the Great Depression of the 1930s, through the years of World War II American art was characterized by Social Realism and American Scene Painting (as seen above) in the work of Grant Wood, Edward Hopper, Ben Shahn, Thomas Hart Benton, and several others.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] *Nighthawks* (1942) is a painting by Edward Hopper that portrays people sitting in a downtown diner late at night.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is not only Hopper's most famous painting, but one of the most recognizable in American art.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is currently in the collection of the Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The scene was inspired by a diner (since demolished) in Greenwich Village, Hopper's home neighborhood in Manhattan.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Hopper began painting it immediately after the attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] After this event there was a large feeling of gloominess over the country, a feeling that is portrayed in the painting.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The urban street is empty outside the diner, and inside none of the three patrons is apparently looking or talking to the others but instead is lost in their own thoughts.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] This portrayal of modern urban life as empty or lonely is a common theme throughout Hopper's work.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The 1940s in New York City heralded the triumph of American abstract expressionism, a modernist movement that combined lessons learned from Henri Matisse, Pablo Picasso, Surrealism, Joan Miró, Cubism, Fauvism, and early Modernism via great teachers in America like Hans Hofmann and John D.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American artists benefited from the presence of Piet Mondrian, Fernand Léger, Max Ernst and the André Breton group, Pierre Matisse's gallery, and Peggy Guggenheim's The Art of This Century Gallery, as well as other factors.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American Abstract Expressionism got its name in 1946 from the art critic Robert Coates.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is seen as combining the emotional intensity and self-denial of the German Expressionists with the anti-figurative aesthetic of the European abstract schools such as Futurism, the Bauhaus and Synthetic Cubism.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract Expressionism, Action painting, and Color Field painting are synonymous with the New York School.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Technically Surrealism was an important predecessor for Abstract expressionism with its emphasis on spontaneous, automatic or subconscious creation.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Jackson Pollock's dripping paint onto a canvas laid on the floor is a technique that has its roots in the work of André Masson.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Another important early manifestation of what came to be abstract expressionism is the work of American Northwest artist Mark Tobey, especially his "white writing" canvases, which, though generally not large in scale, anticipate the "all over" look of Pollock's drip paintings.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Additionally, abstract expressionism has an image of being rebellious, anarchic, highly idiosyncratic and, some feel, rather nihilistic.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In practice, the term is applied to any number of artists working (mostly) in New York who had quite different styles, and even applied to work which is not especially abstract nor expressionist.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Pollock's energetic "action paintings", with their "busy" feel, are different both technically and aesthetically, to the violent and grotesque *Women* series of Willem de Kooning.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As seen above in the gallery *Woman V* is one of a series of six paintings made by de Kooning between 1950 and 1953 that depict a three-quarter-length female figure.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He began the first of these paintings, *Woman I* collection: The Museum of Modern Art, New York City, in June 1950, repeatedly changing and painting out the image until January or February 1952, when the painting was abandoned unfinished.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The art historian Meyer Schapiro saw the painting in de Kooning's studio soon afterwards and encouraged the artist to persist.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] De Kooning's response was to begin three other paintings on the same theme; *Woman II*, The Museum of Modern Art, New York City, *Woman III*, Tehran Museum of Contemporary Art, *Woman IV*, Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art, Kansas City, Missouri.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the summer of 1952, spent at East Hampton, de Kooning further explored the theme through drawings and pastels.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He may have finished work on *Woman I* by the end of June, or possibly as late as November 1952, and probably the other three women pictures were concluded at much the same time.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The *Woman series* are decidedly figurative paintings.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Both Hans Hofmann and Robert Motherwell (gallery) can be comfortably described as practitioners of action painting and Color field painting.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract expressionism has many stylistic similarities to the Russian artists of the early twentieth century such as Wassily Kandinsky.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Although it is true that spontaneity or of the impression of spontaneity characterized many of the abstract expressionists works, most of these paintings involved careful planning, especially since their large size demanded it.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] An exception might be the drip paintings of Pollock.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Why this style gained mainstream acceptance in the 1950s is a matter of debate.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American Social realism had been the mainstream in the 1930s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It had been influenced not only by the Great Depression but also by the Social Realists of Mexico such as David Alfaro Siqueiros and Diego Rivera.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The political climate after World War II did not long tolerate the social protests of those painters.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract expressionism arose during World War II and began to be showcased during the early 1940s at galleries in New York like The Art of This Century Gallery.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The late 1940s through the mid-1950s ushered in the McCarthy era.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It was after World War II and a time of political conservatism and extreme artistic censorship in the United States.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Some people have conjectured that since the subject matter was often totally abstract, Abstract expressionism became a safe strategy for artists to pursue this style.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract art could be seen as apolitical.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Or if the art was political, the message was largely for the insiders.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] However those theorists are in the minority.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As the first truly original school of painting in America, Abstract expressionism demonstrated the vitality and creativity of the country in the post-war years, as well as its ability (or need) to develop an aesthetic sense that was not constrained by the European standards of beauty.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Although Abstract expressionism spread quickly throughout the United States, the major centers of this style were New York City and California, especially in the New York School, and the San Francisco Bay area.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract expressionist paintings share certain characteristics, including the use of large canvases, an "all-over" approach, in which the whole canvas is treated with equal importance (as opposed to the center being of more interest than the edges).
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The canvas as the *arena* became a credo of Action painting, while the *integrity of the picture plane* became a credo of the Color Field painters.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1950s, Color Field painting initially referred to a particular type of abstract expressionism, especially the work of Mark Rothko, Clyfford Still, Barnett Newman, Robert Motherwell and Adolph Gottlieb.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It essentially involved abstract paintings with large, flat expanses of color that expressed the sensual, and visual feelings and properties of large areas of nuanced surface.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Art critic Clement Greenberg perceived Color Field painting as related to but different from Action painting.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The overall expanse and gestalt of the work of the early color field painters speaks of an almost religious experience, awestruck in the face of an expanding universe of sensuality, color and surface.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Artists like Clyfford Still, Mark Rothko, Hans Hofmann, Morris Louis, Jules Olitski, Kenneth Noland, Helen Frankenthaler, Larry Zox, and others often used greatly reduced references to nature, and they painted with a highly articulated and psychological use of color.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In general these artists eliminated recognizable imagery.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In *Mountains and Sea,* from 1952, a seminal work of Colorfield painting by Helen Frankenthaler the artist used the stain technique for the first time.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In Europe there was the continuation of Surrealism, Cubism, Dada and the works of Matisse.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Also in Europe, Tachisme (the European equivalent to Abstract expressionism) and Informalism took hold of the newest generation.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Serge Poliakoff, Nicolas de Staël, Georges Mathieu, Vieira da Silva, Jean Dubuffet, Yves Klein and Pierre Soulages among others are considered important figures in post-war European painting.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Eventually abstract painting in America evolved into movements such as Neo-Dada, Color Field painting, Post painterly abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Minimal art, shaped canvas painting, Lyrical Abstraction, Neo-expressionism and the continuation of Abstract expressionism.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As a response to the tendency toward abstraction imagery emerged through various new movements, notably Pop art.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1930s through the 1960s as abstract painting in America and Europe evolved into movements such as Abstract Expressionism, Color Field painting, Post painterly abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Minimal art, shaped canvas painting, and Lyrical abstraction.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Other artists reacted as a response to the tendency toward abstraction allowing imagery to continue through various new contexts like the Bay Area Figurative Movement in the 1950s and new forms of expressionism from the 1940s through the 1960s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In Italy during this time, Giorgio Morandi was the foremost still life painter, exploring a wide variety of approaches to depicting everyday bottles and kitchen implements.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Throughout the 20th century many painters practiced Realism and used expressive imagery; practicing landscape and figurative painting with contemporary subjects and solid technique, and unique expressivity like Milton Avery, John D.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Graham, Fairfield Porter, Edward Hopper, Andrew Wyeth, Balthus, Francis Bacon, Frank Auerbach, Lucian Freud, Leon Kossoff, Philip Pearlstein, Willem de Kooning, Arshile Gorky, Grace Hartigan, Robert De Niro, Sr., Elaine de Kooning and others.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Along with Henri Matisse, Pablo Picasso, Pierre Bonnard, Georges Braque, and other 20th-century masters.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The figurative work of Francis Bacon, Frida Kahlo, Edward Hopper, Lucian Freud Andrew Wyeth and others served as a kind of alternative to abstract expressionism.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] One of the most well-known images in 20th-century American art is Wyeth's painting, *Christina's World*, currently in the collection of the Museum of Modern Art in New York City.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It depicts a woman lying on the ground in a treeless, mostly tawny field, looking up at and crawling towards a gray house on the horizon; a barn and various other small outbuildings are adjacent to the house.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] This tempera work, done in a realist style, is nearly always on display at the Museum of Modern Art in New York.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Arshile Gorky's portrait of what may be his friend Willem de Kooning (left) is an example of the evolution of Abstract Expressionism from the context of figure painting, cubism and surrealism.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Along with his friends de Kooning and John D.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Graham Gorky created bio-morphically shaped and abstracted figurative compositions that by the 1940s evolved into totally abstract paintings.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Gorky's work seems to be a careful analysis of memory, emotion and shape, using line and color to express feeling and nature.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] After World War II the term School of Paris often referred to Tachisme, the European equivalent of American Abstract expressionism and those artists are also related to Cobra.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1952 Michel Tapié authored the book *Un Autre art* which gave name and voice to Informalism.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Important proponents being Jean Dubuffet, Pierre Soulages, Nicolas de Staël, Hans Hartung, Serge Poliakoff, and Georges Mathieu, among several others.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the early 1950s Dubuffet (who was always a figurative artist), and de Staël, abandoned abstraction, and returned to imagery via figuration and landscape.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] De Staël 's work was quickly recognised within the post-war art world, and he became one of the most influential artists of the 1950s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Much of de Staël 's late work – in particular his thinned, and diluted oil on canvas abstract landscapes of the mid-1950s predicts Color Field painting and Lyrical Abstraction of the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Nicolas de Staël's bold and intensely vivid color in his last paintings predict the direction of much of contemporary painting that came after him including Pop art of the 1960s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Pop art in America was to a large degree initially inspired by the works of Jasper Johns, Larry Rivers, and Robert Rauschenberg.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Although the paintings of Gerald Murphy, Stuart Davis and Charles Demuth during the 1920s and 1930s set the table for Pop art in America.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In New York City during the mid-1950s Robert Rauschenberg and Jasper Johns created works of art that at first seemed to be continuations of Abstract expressionist painting.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Actually their works and the work of Larry Rivers, were radical departures from abstract expressionism especially in the use of banal and literal imagery and the inclusion and the combining of mundane materials into their work.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Eventually by 1963 the movement came to be known worldwide as Pop art.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Pop art is exemplified by artists: Andy Warhol, Claes Oldenburg, Wayne Thiebaud, James Rosenquist, Jim Dine, Tom Wesselmann and Roy Lichtenstein among others.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lichtenstein used oil and Magna paint in his best known works, such as *Drowning Girl* (1963), which was appropriated from the lead story in DC Comics' *Secret Hearts* #83.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] (*Drowning Girl* now is in the collection of Museum of Modern Art, New York.) Also featuring thick outlines, bold colors and Ben-Day dots to represent certain colors, as if created by photographic reproduction.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lichtenstein would say of his own work: Abstract Expressionists "put things down on the canvas and responded to what they had done, to the color positions and sizes.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In October 1962 the Sidney Janis Gallery mounted *The New Realists* the first major Pop art group exhibition in an uptown art gallery in New York City.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Sidney Janis mounted the exhibition in a 57th Street storefront near his gallery at 15 E.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The show sent shockwaves through the New York School and reverberated worldwide.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Earlier in the fall of 1962 a historically important and ground-breaking *New Painting of Common Objects* exhibition of Pop art, curated by Walter Hopps at the Pasadena Art Museum sent shock waves across the Western United States.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] *Campbell's Soup Cans* (sometimes referred to as *32 Campbell's Soup Cans*) is the title of an Andy Warhol work of art that was produced in 1962.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] It consists of thirty-two canvases, each measuring 20 inches in height x 16 inches in width (50.8 x 40.6 cm) and each consisting of a painting of a Campbell's Soup can—one of each canned soup variety the company offered at the time.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The individual paintings were produced with a semi-mechanised silkscreen process, using a non-painterly style.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] They helped usher in Pop art as a major art movement that relied on themes from popular culture.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These works by Andy Warhol are repetitive and they are made in a non-painterly commercial manner.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Earlier in England in 1956 the term *Pop Art* was used by Lawrence Alloway for paintings that celebrated consumerism of the post World War II era.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This movement rejected Abstract expressionism and its focus on the hermeneutic and psychological interior, in favor of art which depicted, and often celebrated material consumer culture, advertising, and iconography of the mass production age.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The early works of David Hockney whose paintings emerged from England during the 1960s like *A Bigger Splash,* and the works of Richard Hamilton, Peter Blake, and Eduardo Paolozzi, are considered seminal examples in the movement.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] While in the downtown scene in New York's East Village 10th Street galleries artists were formulating an American version of Pop art.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Claes Oldenburg had his storefront, and the Green Gallery on 57th Street began to show Tom Wesselmann and James Rosenquist.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Later Leo Castelli exhibited other American artists including the bulk of the careers of Andy Warhol and Roy Lichtenstein and his use of Benday dots, a technique used in commercial reproduction and seen in ordinary comic books and in paintings like *Drowning Girl*, 1963, in the gallery above.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] There is a connection between the radical works of Duchamp, and Man Ray, the rebellious Dadaists – with a sense of humor; and Pop Artists like Alex Katz (who became known for his parodies of portrait photography and suburban life), Claes Oldenburg, Andy Warhol, Roy Lichtenstein and the others.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1950s and 1960s as abstract painting in America and Europe evolved into movements such as Color Field painting, Post painterly abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Minimal art, shaped canvas painting, Lyrical Abstraction, and the continuation of Abstract expressionism.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] 1),* 1963, Oil on canvas, 60 1/4 x 50 1/2 inches, collection: San Francisco Museum of Modern Art), and later in the 1970s Neo-expressionism.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Bay Area Figurative Movement of whom David Park, Elmer Bischoff, Nathan Oliveira and Richard Diebenkorn whose painting *Cityscape 1,* 1963 is a typical example were influential members flourished during the 1950s and 1960s in California.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Younger painters practiced the use of imagery in new and radical ways.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Yves Klein, Martial Raysse, Niki de Saint Phalle, David Hockney, Alex Katz, Antoni Tàpies, Malcolm Morley, Ralph Goings, Audrey Flack, Richard Estes, Chuck Close, Susan Rothenberg, Eric Fischl, John Baeder, and Vija Celmins were a few who became prominent between the 1960s and the 1980s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Fairfield Porter was largely self-taught, and produced representational work in the midst of the Abstract Expressionist movement.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His subjects were primarily landscapes, domestic interiors and portraits of family, friends and fellow artists, many of them affiliated with the New York School of writers, including John Ashbery, Frank O'Hara, and James Schuyler.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Many of his paintings were set in or around the family summer house on Great Spruce Head Island, Maine.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Neo-Dada is a movement that started in the 1950s and 1960s and was related to Abstract expressionism only with imagery.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Featuring the emergence of combined manufactured items, with artist materials, moving away from previous conventions of painting.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This trend in art is exemplified by the work of Jasper Johns and Robert Rauschenberg, whose "combines" in the 1950s were forerunners of Pop Art and Installation art, and made use of the assemblage of large physical objects, including stuffed animals, birds and commercial photography.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1960s and 1970s abstract painting continued to develop in America through varied styles.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Geometric abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Color Field painting and minimal painting, were some interrelated directions for advanced abstract painting as well as some other new movements.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Morris Louis was an important pioneer in advanced Colorfield painting, his work can serve as a bridge between Abstract expressionism, Colorfield painting, and Minimal Art.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Two influential teachers Josef Albers and Hans Hofmann introduced a new generation of American artists to their advanced theories of color and space.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Josef Albers is best remembered for his work as a Geometric abstractionist painter and theorist.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Most famous are the hundreds of paintings and prints that make up the series *Homage to the Square*.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In this rigorous series, begun in 1949, Albers explored chromatic interactions with flat colored squares arranged concentrically on the canvas.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Albers' theories on art and education were formative for the next generation of artists.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His own paintings form the foundation of both hard-edge painting and Op art.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Many Geometric abstract artists, minimalists, and Hard-edge painters elected to use the edges of the image to define the shape of the painting rather than accepting the rectangular format.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In fact, the use of the shaped canvas is primarily associated with paintings of the 1960s and 1970s that are coolly abstract, formalistic, geometrical, objective, rationalistic, clean-lined, brashly sharp-edged, or minimalist in character.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Bykert Gallery, and the Park Place Gallery were important showcases for Minimalism and shaped canvas painting in New York City during the 1960s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In 1965, an exhibition called *The Responsive Eye*, curated by William C.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Seitz, was held at the Museum of Modern Art, in New York City.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The works shown were wide-ranging, encompassing the Minimalism of Frank Stella, the Op art of Larry Poons, the work of Alexander Liberman, alongside the masters of the Op Art movement: Victor Vasarely, Richard Anuszkiewicz, Bridget Riley and others.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The exhibition focused on the perceptual aspects of art, which result both from the illusion of movement and the interaction of color relationships.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art, also known as optical art, is a style present in some paintings and other works of art that use optical illusions.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art is also closely akin to geometric abstraction and hard-edge painting.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Although sometimes the term used for it is perceptual abstraction.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art is a method of painting concerning the interaction between illusion and picture plane, between understanding and seeing.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art works are abstract, with many of the better known pieces made in only black and white.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] When the viewer looks at them, the impression is given of movement, hidden images, flashing and vibration, patterns, or alternatively, of swelling or warping.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Color Field painting clearly pointed toward a new direction in American painting, away from abstract expressionism.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Color Field painting is related to Post-painterly abstraction, Suprematism, Abstract Expressionism, Hard-edge painting and Lyrical Abstraction.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Color Field painting sought to rid art of superfluous rhetoric.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Certain artists made references to past or present art, but in general color field painting presents abstraction as an end in itself.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In pursuing this direction of modern art, artists wanted to present each painting as one unified, cohesive, monolithic image.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Frank Stella, Kenneth Noland, Ellsworth Kelly, Barnett Newman, Ronald Davis, Neil Williams, Robert Mangold, Charles Hinman, Richard Tuttle, David Novros, and Alvin Loving are examples of artists associated with the use of the shaped canvas during the period beginning in the early 1960s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] From 1960 Frank Stella produced paintings in aluminium and copper paint and are his first works using shaped canvases (canvases in a shape other than the traditional rectangle or square), often being in L, N, U or T-shapes.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These later developed into more elaborate designs, in the *Irregular Polygon* series (67), for example.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Also in the 1960s, Stella began to use a wider range of colors, typically arranged in straight or curved lines.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Later he began his *Protractor Series* (71) of paintings, in which arcs, sometimes overlapping, within square borders are arranged side-by-side to produce full and half circles painted in rings of concentric color.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] *Harran II,* 1967, is an example of the *Protractor Series*.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These paintings are named after circular cities he had visited while in the Middle East earlier in the 1960s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Irregular Polygon canvases and Protractor series further extended the concept of the shaped canvas.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Andre Emmerich Gallery, the Leo Castelli Gallery, the Richard Feigen Gallery, and the Park Place Gallery were important showcases for Color Field painting, shaped canvas painting and Lyrical Abstraction in New York City during the 1960s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1960s Color Field painting and Minimal art were often closely associated with each other.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In actuality by the early 1970s both movements became decidedly diverse.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Another related movement of the late 1960s, Lyrical Abstraction (the term being coined by Larry Aldrich, the founder of the Aldrich Contemporary Art Museum, Ridgefield Connecticut), encompassed what Aldrich said he saw in the studios of many artists at that time.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] It is also the name of an exhibition that originated in the Aldrich Museum and traveled to the Whitney Museum of American Art and other museums throughout the United States between 1969 and 1971.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Postminimalism often incorporating industrial materials, raw materials, fabrications, found objects, installation, serial repetition, and often with references to Dada and Surrealism is best exemplified in the sculptures of Eva Hesse.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lyrical Abstraction is a type of freewheeling abstract painting that emerged in the mid-1960s when abstract painters returned to various forms of painterly, pictorial, expressionism with a predominate focus on process, gestalt and repetitive compositional strategies in general.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lyrical Abstraction shares similarities with Color Field painting and Abstract Expressionism especially in the freewheeling usage of paint – texture and surface.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Direct drawing, calligraphic use of line, the effects of brushed, splattered, stained, squeegeed, poured, and splashed paint superficially resemble the effects seen in Abstract Expressionism and Color Field painting.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] However the styles are markedly different.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Setting it apart from Abstract Expressionism and Action Painting of the 1940s and 1950s is the approach to composition and drama.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] As seen in Action Painting there is an emphasis on brushstrokes, high compositional drama, dynamic compositional tension.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] While in Lyrical Abstraction as exemplified by the 1971 Ronnie Landfield painting *Garden of Delight* (above), there is a sense of compositional randomness, all over composition, low key and relaxed compositional drama and an emphasis on process, repetition, and an all over sensibility.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Donald Judd had started as a painter, and ended as a creator of objects.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His seminal essay, "Specific Objects" (published in Arts Yearbook 8, 1965), was a touchstone of theory for the formation of Minimalist aesthetics.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In this essay, Judd found a starting point for a new territory for American art, and a simultaneous rejection of residual inherited European artistic values.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] He pointed to evidence of this development in the works of an array of artists active in New York at the time, including Jasper Johns, Dan Flavin and Lee Bontecou.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Of "preliminary" importance for Judd was the work of George Earl Ortman, who had concretized and distilled painting's forms into blunt, tough, philosophically charged geometries.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These Specific Objects inhabited a space not then comfortably classifiable as either painting or sculpture.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] That the categorical identity of such objects was itself in question, and that they avoided easy association with well-worn and over-familiar conventions, was a part of their value for Judd.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] American painters such as Brice Marden and Cy Twombly show a clear European influence in their *pure* abstraction, minimalist painting of the 1960s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Ronald Davis polyurethane works from the late 1960s pay homage to the *Broken Glass* of Marcel Duchamp.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This movement was heavily criticised by high modernist formalist art critics and historians.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Some anxious critics thought Minimalist art represented a misunderstanding of the modern dialectic of painting and sculpture as defined by critic Clement Greenberg, arguably the dominant American critic of painting in the period leading up to the 1960s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The most notable critique of Minimalism was produced by Michael Fried, a Greenbergian critic, who objected to the work on the basis of its "theatricality".
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In *Art and Objecthood* (published in Artforum in June 1967) he declared that the Minimalist work of art, particularly Minimalist sculpture, was based on an engagement with the physicality of the spectator.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] He argued that work like Robert Morris's transformed the act of viewing into a type of spectacle, in which the artifice of the act observation and the viewer's participation in the work were unveiled.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Fried saw this displacement of the viewer's experience from an aesthetic engagement within, to an event outside of the artwork as a failure of Minimal art.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Ad Reinhardt, actually an artist of the Abstract Expressionist generation, but one whose reductive all-black paintings seemed to anticipate minimalism, had this to say about the value of a reductive approach to art: "The more stuff in it, the busier the work of art, the worse it is.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Still other important innovations in abstract painting took place during the 1960s and the 1970s characterized by monochrome painting and hard-edge painting inspired by Ad Reinhardt, Barnett Newman, Milton Resnick, and Ellsworth Kelly.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Artists as diverse as Agnes Martin, Al Held, Larry Zox, Frank Stella, Larry Poons, Brice Marden and others explored the power of simplification.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The convergence of Color Field painting, minimal art, hard-edge painting, Lyrical Abstraction, and postminimalism blurred the distinction between movements that became more apparent in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The neo-expressionism movement is related to earlier developments in abstract expressionism, neo-Dada, Lyrical Abstraction and postminimal painting.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These works were inspirational to a new generation of painters interested in a revival of expressive imagery.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His painting *Painting, Smoking, Eating* 1973, seen above in the gallery is an example of Guston's final and conclusive return to representation.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In the late 1970s and early 1980s, there was also a return to painting that occurred almost simultaneously in Italy, Germany, France and Britain.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These movements were called Transavantguardia, Neue Wilde, Figuration Libre, Neo-expressionism, the school of London, and in the late 1990s the Stuckists, a group that emerged late in 1990s respectively.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These painting were characterized by large formats, free expressive mark making, figuration, myth and imagination.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] All work in this genre came to be labeled neo-expressionism.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Some critics regarded it as driven by profit motivations by large commercial galleries.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This type of art continues in popularity into the 21st century, even after the art crash of the late 1980s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the late 1970s in the United States painters who began working with invigorated surfaces and who returned to imagery like Susan Rothenberg gained in popularity, especially as seen above in paintings like *Horse 2,* 1979.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1980s American artists like Eric Fischl, David Salle, Jean-Michel Basquiat (who began as a graffiti artist), Julian Schnabel, and Keith Haring, and Italian painters like Mimmo Paladino, Sandro Chia, and Enzo Cucchi, among others defined the idea of Neo-expressionism in America.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Neo-expressionism was a style of modern painting that became popular in the late 1970s and dominated the art market until the mid-1980s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] It developed in Europe as a reaction against the conceptual and minimalistic art of the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Neo-expressionists returned to portraying recognizable objects, such as the human body (although sometimes in a virtually abstract manner), in a rough and violently emotional way using vivid colours and banal colour harmonies.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The veteran painters Philip Guston, Frank Auerbach, Leon Kossoff, Gerhard Richter, A.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Penck and Georg Baselitz, along with slightly younger artists like Anselm Kiefer, Eric Fischl, Susan Rothenberg, Francesco Clemente, Damien Hirst, Jean-Michel Basquiat, Julian Schnabel, Keith Haring, and many others became known for working in this intense expressionist vein of painting.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] At the beginning of the 21st century Contemporary painting and Contemporary art in general continues in several contiguous modes, characterized by the idea of pluralism.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Mainstream painting has been rejected by artists of the postmodern era in favor of artistic pluralism.
[src:age-of-discovery/20th-century-western-painting-p02] According to art critic Arthur Danto there is an *anything goes* attitude that prevails; an "everything going on", and consequently "nothing going on" syndrome; this creates an aesthetic traffic jam with no firm and clear direction and with every lane on the artistic superhighway filled to capacity.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] 1620), also known as the **Age of Exploration**, was part of the early modern period and overlapped with the Age of Sail.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] It was a period from approximately the 15th to the 17th century, during which seafarers from European countries explored, colonized, and conquered regions across the globe.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery was a transformative period when previously isolated parts of the world became connected to form the world-system, and laid the groundwork for globalization.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The extensive overseas exploration, particularly the opening of maritime routes to the East Indies and European colonization of the Americas by the Spaniards and Portuguese, later joined by the English, French, and Dutch, spurred international global trade.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The interconnected global economy of the 21st century has its origins in the expansion of trade networks during this era.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The exploration created European colonial empires and marked an increased adoption of colonialism as a government policy in several European states.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] As such, it is sometimes synonymous with the first wave of European colonization.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] This colonization reshaped power dynamics causing geopolitical shifts in Europe and creating new centers of power beyond Europe.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Portuguese oceanic exploration began with maritime expeditions to the Macaronesian islands, including the Canary Islands, as well as Madeira and the Azores.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] It continued with voyages along the coast of West Africa in 1434, and culminated in the establishment of a sea route to India in 1498 by Vasco da Gama, which initiated Portugal's maritime and commercial presence in Kerala and the Indian Ocean.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Spain also undertook other major early voyages, including the conquest of Mexico (1519–1521), the conquest of Peru (1532–1533), and the Manila galleon trade route (1565–1815), which linked the Americas and Asia across the Pacific.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] European exploration initiated the Columbian exchange between the Old World (Europe, Asia, and Africa) and New World (Americas).
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] This exchange involved the transfer of plants, animals, human populations (including slaves), communicable diseases, and culture across the Eastern and Western Hemispheres.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery and European exploration involved mapping the world, shaping a new worldview and facilitating contact with distant civilizations.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The continents drawn by European mapmakers developed from abstract "blobs" into the outlines more recognizable to us.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Simultaneously, the spread of new diseases, especially affecting American Indians, led to rapid declines in some populations.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The era saw widespread enslavement, exploitation and military conquest of Indigenous peoples, concurrent with the growing economic influence and spread of Western culture, science, and technology leading to a faster-than-exponential population growth world-wide.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of discovery has been scrutinized, critically highlighting the history of the core term of this periodization.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The term "age of discovery" is in historical literature and still commonly used.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Something of which they had no prior knowledge had suddenly presented itself to their gaze." O'Gorman argues that the physical encounter with new territories was less important than the Europeans' effort to integrate this new knowledge into their worldview, what he calls "the invention of America".
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Pagden examines the origins of the terms "discovery" and "invention".
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In English, "discovery" and its forms in romance languages derive from "*disco-operio*, meaning to uncover, to reveal, to expose to the gaze", what was revealed existed previously.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Few Europeans during the period used the term "invention" for the European encounters, with the exception of Martin Waldseemüller, whose map first used the term "America".
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] A central legal concept of the discovery doctrine, expounded by the United States Supreme Court in 1823, draws on assertions of European powers' right to claim land during their explorations.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of "discovery" has been used to enforce colonial claiming and discovery, but has been challenged by Indigenous peoples and researchers.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Many indigenous peoples have fundamentally challenged the concept of colonial claiming of "discovery" over their lands and people, as forced and negating indigenous presence.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The period alternatively called the *Age of Exploration*, has been scrutinized through reflections on the exploration.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Its understanding and use, has been discussed as being framed and used for colonial ventures, discrimination and exploitation, by combining it with concepts such as the frontier (as in Frontier Thesis) and manifest destiny, up to the contemporary age of space exploration.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Alternatively, the term *contact*, as in first contact, has been used to shed more light on the age of discovery and colonialism, using the alternative names of *Age of Contact* or *Contact Period*, discussing it as an "unfinished, diverse project".
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese began systematically exploring the Atlantic coast of Africa in 1418, under the sponsorship of Prince Henry the Navigator.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1488, Bartolomeu Dias reached the Indian Ocean by this route.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1492, the Catholic Monarchs of Spain funded Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus's (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) plan to sail west to reach the Indies, by crossing the Atlantic.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus encountered a continent uncharted by Europeans (though it had been explored and temporarily colonized by the Norse 500 years earlier).
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Later, it was called America after Amerigo Vespucci, a trader working for Portugal.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal quickly claimed those lands under the terms of the Treaty of Alcáçovas, but Castile was able to persuade the Pope, who was Castilian, to issue four papal bulls to divide the world into two regions of exploration, where each kingdom had exclusive rights to claim newly discovered lands.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] These were modified by the Treaty of Tordesillas, ratified by Pope Julius II.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1498, a Portuguese expedition commanded by Vasco da Gama reached India by sailing around Africa, opening up direct trade with Asia.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese sailed further eastward, to the valuable Spice Islands in 1512, landing in China one year later.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Japan was reached by the Portuguese in 1543.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1513, Spanish explorer Vasco Núñez de Balboa crossed the Isthmus of Panama and reached the "other sea" from the New World.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Thus, Europe first received news of the eastern and western Pacific within a one-year span around 1512.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] East and west exploration overlapped in 1522, when a Spanish expedition sailing westward, led by Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan (and, after his death in what is now the Philippines, by navigator Juan Sebastián Elcano), completed the first circumnavigation of the world.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Spanish *conquistadors* explored the interior of the Americas, and some of the South Pacific islands.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Their main objective was to disrupt Portuguese trade in the East.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1495, the French, English, and Dutch entered the race of exploration, after learning of Columbus' exploits, defying the Iberian monopoly on maritime trade by searching for new routes.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The first expedition was led by John Cabot in 1497 to the north, in the service of England, followed by French expeditions to South America and later to North America.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Later expeditions went to the Pacific Ocean around South America, and eventually by following the Portuguese around Africa, into the Indian Ocean; discovering Australia in 1606, New Zealand in 1642, and Hawaii in 1778.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 1580s to the 1640s, Russians explored and conquered almost the whole of Siberia, and claimed Alaska in the 1730s.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire largely severed the connection between Europe and lands further east, Christian Europe was largely a backwater compared to the Muslim world, which conquered and incorporated large territories in the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Christian Crusades to retake the Holy Land from the Muslims were not a military success, but they did bring Europe into contact with the Middle East and the valuable goods manufactured or traded there.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 12th century, the European economy was transformed by the interconnecting of river and sea trade routes.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Economic growth of Iberia followed the Christian reconquest of Al-Andalus in what is now southern Spain and the siege of Lisbon (1147 AD), in Portugal.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The decline of the Fatimid Caliphate's naval strength, which started before the First Crusade, helped the maritime Italian states, mainly Venice, Genoa and Pisa, dominate trade in the Eastern Mediterranean, with merchants there becoming wealthy and politically influential.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Norman conquest of England, in the late 11th century, allowed for peaceful trade on the North Sea.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Hanseatic League, a confederation of merchant guilds and their towns in north Germany, along the North Sea and Baltic Sea, was instrumental in the commercial development of the region.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In the 12th century, the regions of Flanders, Hainault, and Brabant produced the finest quality textiles in northwest Europe, which encouraged merchants from Genoa and Venice to sail there from the Mediterranean, through the Strait of Gibraltar, and up the Atlantic coast.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Nicolòzzo Spinola made the first recorded direct voyage from Genoa to Flanders in 1277.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Technological advancements that were important to the Age of Exploration were the adoption of the magnetic compass and advances in ship design.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass was an addition to the ancient method of navigation based on sightings of the sun and stars.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] It was invented during the Chinese Han dynasty and had been used for navigation in China by the 11th century.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] It was adopted by Arab traders in the Indian Ocean.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass spread to Europe by the late 12th or early 13th century.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Use of the compass for navigation in the Indian Ocean was first mentioned in 1232.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The first mention of use of the compass in Europe was in 1180.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Europeans used a "dry" compass, with a needle on a pivot.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass card was also a European invention.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The ships of the Age of Discovery post-dated the fusion of the northern European and Mediterranean shipbuilding traditions.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to the late 13th/early 14th centuries, northern European ships were typically clinker built, with a single mast setting a square sail and a centre-line rudder hung on the sternpost with pintles and gudgeons.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Their counterparts in the Mediterranean were built with carvel hulls, had one or more masts (depending on size) which set lateen sails, and were steered with quarter-rudders positioned on the side of the hull.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Trade, pilgrimage and war brought ships from each tradition into the other's region, ultimately leading to the copying of features that were new to each.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Over the early 14th century, square sails started to be used in the Mediterranean, with the mainmast setting square rig and the mizzen carrying a lateen sail.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In the first two decades of the 15th century this arrangement was copied in northern Europe where, by the late 1430s, some ships were built with carvel hulls.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The result of this merging of traditions was the full-rigged ship, a carvel hull with a sternpost-hung pintle-and-gudgeon rudder and three masts: the foremast and mainmast setting square sails and the mizzen a lateen sail.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Alongside this type of vessel, the caravel was used.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] This type was also carvel built with a sternpost-hung rudder but could be completely lateen rigged or have some square sails.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Very few wrecks of Age of Discovery ships have been found and archaeologically investigated.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] More is known about Roman and Greek ships of classical antiquity than those of this period.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The caravel is particularly poorly understood, despite the number of "replicas" that have been constructed.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] However, a particular set of hull construction characteristics have been identified from wrecks of this time, referred to as Iberian Atlantic shipbuilding tradition.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] They are found in the Molasses Reef wreck, Highbourne Cay wreck, the Red Bay wreck and some sites in European waters.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] European medieval knowledge about Asia beyond the reach of the Byzantine Empire was sourced in partial reports, often obscured by legends, dating back from the conquests of Alexander the Great and successors.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Another source was the Radhanite Jewish trade networks of merchants established as go-betweens between Europe and the Muslim world during the time of the Crusader states.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] There were reports of great African Sahara, but the knowledge was limited for the Europeans, to the Mediterranean coast and little else, since the Arab blockade of North Africa precluded exploration inland.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Knowledge about the Atlantic African coast was fragmented and derived mainly from old Greek and Roman maps based on Carthaginian knowledge, including Roman exploration of Mauritania.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Red Sea was barely known and only trade links with the maritime republics, Venice especially, fostered the collection of accurate maritime knowledge.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Indian Ocean trade routes were sailed by Arab traders.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] By 1400, a Latin translation of Ptolemy's *Geographia* reached Italy from Constantinople.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The rediscovery of Roman geographical knowledge was a revelation, both for map-making and worldview, although reinforcing the idea that the Indian Ocean was landlocked.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] A prelude to the Age of Discovery was a series of European expeditions crossing Eurasia by land in the late Middle Ages.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongols had threatened Europe, but Mongol states also unified much of Eurasia and, from 1206 on, the *Pax Mongolica* allowed safe trade routes and communication lines from the Middle East to China.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The close Italian links to the Levant raised curiosity and commercial interest in countries which lay further east.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] There are a few accounts of merchants from North Africa and the Mediterranean, who traded in the Indian Ocean in late medieval times (see also Indo-Mediterranean § Medieval era).
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Christian embassies were sent as far as Karakorum during the Mongol invasions of the Levant, from which they gained a greater understanding of the world.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The first of these travellers was Giovanni da Pian del Carpine, dispatched by Pope Innocent IV to the Great Khan, who journeyed to Mongolia and back from 1241 to 1247.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Russian prince Yaroslav of Vladimir, and his sons Alexander Nevsky and Andrey II of Vladimir, travelled to the Mongolian capital.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Though having strong political implications, their journeys left no detailed accounts.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Other travellers followed, like French André de Longjumeau and Flemish William of Rubruck, who reached China through Central Asia.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Marco Polo, a Venetian merchant, dictated an account of journeys throughout Asia from 1271 to 1295, describing being a guest at the Yuan dynasty court of Kublai Khan in *Travels*.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim fleet guarding the Strait of Gibraltar was defeated by Genoa in 1291.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In that year, the Genoese attempted their first Atlantic exploration when merchant brothers Vadino and Ugolino Vivaldi sailed from Genoa with two galleys, but disappeared off the Moroccan coast, feeding fears of oceanic travel.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1325 to 1354, a Moroccan scholar from Tangier, Ibn Battuta, journeyed through North Africa, the Sahara desert, West Africa, Southern Europe, Eastern Europe, the Horn of Africa, the Middle East, and Asia, having reached China.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] After returning, he dictated an account to a scholar he met in Granada, *The Rihla* ("The Journey"), the unheralded source on his adventures.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1357 and 1371, a book of supposed travels compiled by John Mandeville acquired popularity.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite the unreliable and often fantastical nature of its accounts, it was used as a reference for the East, Egypt, and the Levant in general, asserting the old belief that Jerusalem was the centre of the world.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the period of Timurid relations with Europe, in 1439, Niccolò de' Conti published an account of his travels as a Muslim merchant to India and Southeast Asia.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1466–1472, Russian merchant Afanasy Nikitin of Tver travelled to India, which he described in his book *A Journey Beyond the Three Seas*.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] These overland journeys had little immediate effect.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongol Empire collapsed almost as quickly as it formed and soon the route to the east became more difficult and dangerous.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Black Death of the 14th century also blocked travel and trade for a time.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Religion played a critical role in motivating European expansionism.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1487, Portuguese envoys Pero da Covilhã and Afonso de Paiva were sent on a covert mission to gather intelligence on a potential sea route to India and inquire about Prester John, a Nestorian patriarch and king, believed to rule over parts of the subcontinent.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Covilhã was warmly received upon his arrival in Ethiopia, but forbidden from leaving.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] During the Middle Ages, the spread of Christianity throughout Europe fueled the desire to sermonise in lands beyond.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] This evangelical effort became a significant part of the military conquests of European powers, like Portugal, Spain, and France, often leading to the conversion of indigenous peoples, voluntarily or forced.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Religious orders such as the Franciscans, Dominicans, Augustinians, and Jesuits partook in most missionary endeavours in the New World.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] By the late 16th and 17th centuries, the latter's presence increased as they sought to reassert their power and revive the Catholic culture of Europe, which had been damaged by the Reformation.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Chinese had wide connections through trade in Asia and been sailing to Arabia, East Africa, and Egypt since the Tang dynasty (AD 618–907).
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1405 and 1421, the third Ming emperor Yongle sponsored long range tributary missions in the Indian Ocean under the command of admiral Zheng He.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] A large fleet of new junk ships was prepared for the international diplomatic expeditions.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The largest of these junks—that the Chinese termed *bao chuan* (treasure ships)—may have measured 121 metres (397 ft), and thousands of sailors were involved.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] At least seven well-documented expeditions were launched, each bigger and more expensive than the last.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleets visited Arabia, East Africa, India, Malay Archipelago, and Thailand (then called Siam), exchanging goods along the way.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] They presented gifts of gold, silver, porcelain, and silk; in return, received such novelties as ostriches, zebras, camels, ivory, and giraffes.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] After the emperor's death, Zheng He led a final expedition departing from Nanking in 1431 and returning to Beijing in 1433.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] It is likely this last expedition reached as far as Madagascar.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The travels were reported by Ma Huan, a Muslim voyager and translator who accompanied Zheng He on three of the expeditions, his account published as the *Yingya Shenglan* (Overall Survey of the Ocean's Shores) (1433).
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages had a significant and lasting effect on the organization of a maritime network, using and creating nodes and conduits in its wake, thereby restructuring international and cross-cultural relationships and exchanges.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] It was especially impactful as no other polity had exerted naval dominance over all sectors of the Indian Ocean, prior to these voyages.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Ming promoted alternative nodes as a strategy to establish control over the network.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] For instance, due to Chinese involvement, ports such as Malacca (in Southeast Asia), Cochin (Malabar Coast), and Malindi (Swahili Coast) had grown as key alternatives to other established ports.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The appearance of the Ming treasure fleet generated and intensified competition among contending polities and rivals, each seeking an alliance with the Ming.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The expeditions developed into a maritime trade enterprise, with imperial control over local markets and court-monitored transactions, generating revenue for China and its partners.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] They boosted regional trade and production, caused a supply shock in Eurasia and led to price spikes in Europe in the early 15th century.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The tributary relations promoted during the voyages manifested a trend toward cross-regional interconnections and early globalization in Asia and Africa.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Diplomatic relations were built on mutually beneficial maritime trade and China's strong naval presence in foreign waters, with Chinese naval superiority being a key factor in these interactions.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages brought about the Western Ocean's regional integration and increase in international circulation of people, ideas, and goods.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] It provided a platform for cosmopolitan discourses, which took place in locations such as the ships of the Ming treasure fleet, the Ming capitals of Nanjing as well as Beijing, and the banquet receptions organized by the Ming court for foreign representatives.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Diverse groups of people from maritime countries congregated, interacted, and traveled together as the treasure fleet sailed from and to China.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first time, the maritime region from China to Africa was under the dominance of a single imperial power and allowed for the creation of a cosmopolitan space.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] These long-distance journeys were not followed up, as the Ming dynasty retreated in the *haijin*, a policy of isolationism, having limited maritime trade.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 8th until the 15th century, the Republic of Venice and neighboring maritime republics held the monopoly of European trade with the Middle East.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The silk and spice trade, involving spices, incense, herbs, drugs, and opium, made these Mediterranean city-states phenomenally rich.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Spices were among the most expensive and demanded products of the Middle Ages, as they were used in medieval medicine, religious rituals, cosmetics, perfumery, and food additives and preservatives.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] They were imported from Asia and Africa.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Muslim traders dominated maritime routes throughout the Indian Ocean, tapping source regions in the Far East and shipping for trading emporiums in India, mainly Calicut, westward to Hormuz in the Persian Gulf and Jeddah in the Red Sea.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] From there, overland routes led to the Mediterranean.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Afterwards, the routes into Asia through the Black Sea and through Armenia and Persia became blocked by wars and banditry as the Mongol states disintegrated.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade route from the Persian Gulf to the Mediterranean by land is also dangerous due to the unstable territorial control of the Mamluk.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade from India went almost entirely into the Red Sea.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Nevertheless, European spices have not become more expensive as a result.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Forced to reduce activity in the Black Sea, and at war with Venice, the Genoese had turned to North African trade of wheat, olive oil and a search for silver and gold.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans had a constant deficit in silver and gold, as it only went out, spent on eastern trade now cut off.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Several European mines were exhausted, The lack of bullion led to the development of a complex banking system to manage the risks in trade (the first state bank, *Banco di San Giorgio*, was founded in 1407 at Genoa).
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing into the ports of Bruges and England, Genoese communities were then established in Portugal, who profited from their enterprise and financial expertise.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] European sailing had been primarily close to land cabotage, guided by portolan charts.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] These charts specified proven ocean routes guided by coastal landmarks: sailors departed from a known point, followed a compass heading, and tried to identify their location by its landmarks.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first oceanic exploration Europeans used the compass, and advances in cartography and astronomy.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Arab navigational tools like the astrolabe and quadrant were used for celestial navigation.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim lands in Asia were more economically developed, had better infrastructure, despite Europe's economic changes brought by the Black Death, allowing for more freedoms.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Islamic gunpowder empires concealed knowledge from European Christian traders about where lucrative locations such as Indonesia were.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1317, King Denis of Portugal made an agreement with Genoese merchant sailor Manuel Pessanha, appointing him first admiral of the Portuguese Navy, to defend the country against Muslim pirate raids.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Outbreaks of bubonic plague led to depopulation in the second half of the 14th century: only the sea offered alternatives, with most population settling in fishing and trading coastal areas.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1325 and 1357, Afonso IV of Portugal encouraged maritime commerce and ordered the first explorations.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Canary Islands, already known to the Genoese, were claimed as officially discovered under the patronage of the Portuguese, but in 1344, Castile disputed them.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] To ensure their trade monopoly, Europeans, beginning with the Portuguese, attempted to install a Mediterranean system of trade which used military intimidation, to divert trade through ports they controlled; there it could be taxed.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1415, Ceuta, in North Africa, was conquered by the Portuguese aiming to control navigation of the African coast.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Young prince Henry the Navigator became aware of profit possibilities in the trans-Saharan trade routes.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] For centuries slave and gold trade routes linking West Africa with the Mediterranean passed over the Western Sahara Desert, controlled by the Moors.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] He invested in sponsoring voyages down the coast of Mauritania, gathering merchants, shipowners and stakeholders interested in new sea lanes.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the Atlantic islands of Madeira (1419) and the Azores (1427) were reached.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition leader who established settlements on Madeira, was explorer João Gonçalves Zarco.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans did not know what lay beyond Cape Non (Cape Chaunar) on the African coast, and whether it was possible to return once crossed.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Nautical myths warned of monsters or an edge of the world, but Henry's navigation challenged such beliefs: starting in 1421, systematic sailing overcame it, reaching the difficult Cape Bojador that in 1434 one of Henry's captains, Gil Eanes, finally passed.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1440, caravels were extensively used for the exploration of the coast of Africa.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] This was an Iberian ship type, used for fishing, commerce and military purposes.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] It had a sternpost-mounted rudder, a shallow draft helpful in exploring coastlines, a good sailing performance, with a windward ability.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The lateen rig was less useful when sailing downwind – which explains Christopher Columbus (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) re-rigging the *Niña* with square rig.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] For celestial navigation the Portuguese used the ephemerides, which experienced a remarkable diffusion in the 15th century.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] These were astronomical charts plotting the location of the stars.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Published in 1496 by Jewish astronomer and mathematician Abraham Zacuto, the Almanac Perpetuum included some of these tables for the movements of stars.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] These revolutionized navigation, allowing the calculation of latitude.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Exact longitude remained elusive from mariners for centuries.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Using the caravel, systematic exploration continued southerly, advancing one degree a year.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Senegal and Cape Verde Peninsula were reached in 1445 and in 1446, Álvaro Fernandes pushed on almost as far as present-day Sierra Leone.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1453, the fall of Constantinople to the Ottomans was a perceived blow to Christendom and established business links with the East.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The king, who had been inquiring of Genoese experts about a seaway to India, commissioned the Fra Mauro world map, which arrived in Lisbon in 1459.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1456, Diogo Gomes reached the Cape Verde archipelago.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In the next decade captains at the service of Prince Henry, discovered the remaining islands which were occupied during the 15th century.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Gulf of Guinea was reached in the 1460s.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1460, Pedro de Sintra reached Sierra Leone.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Prince Henry died in November after which, given the meagre revenues, exploration was granted to Lisbon merchant Fernão Gomes in 1469, who in exchange for the monopoly of trade in the Gulf of Guinea had to explore 100 miles (161 kilometres) each year for five years.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] With his sponsorship, explorers João de Santarém, Pedro Escobar, Lopo Gonçalves, Fernão do Pó, and Pedro de Sintra made it beyond those goals.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] They reached the Southern Hemisphere and islands of the Gulf of Guinea, including São Tomé and Príncipe and Elmina in 1471.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] There, in what came to be called the "Gold Coast", in today's Ghana, a thriving alluvial gold trade was found among the natives, Arab and Berber traders.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1478, during the War of the Castilian Succession, near the coast at Elmina a large battle was fought between a Castilian armada of 35 caravels, and a Portuguese fleet for the hegemony of the Guinea trade.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The war ended with a Portuguese victory, followed by official recognition by the Catholic Monarchs of Portuguese sovereignty over most of the disputed West African territories embodied in the Treaty of Alcáçovas, 1479.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1481, João II decided to build São Jorge da Mina factory.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1482, the Congo River was explored by Diogo Cão, who in 1486 continued to Cape Cross (modern Namibia).
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The next crucial breakthrough was in 1488, when Bartolomeu Dias rounded the southern tip of Africa, which he named Cabo das Tormentas, "Cape of Storms", then sailing east as far as the mouth of the Great Fish River, proving the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Pero da Covilhã, sent out travelling secretly overland, had reached Ethiopia having collected important information about the Red Sea and Quenia coast, suggesting a sea route to the Indies would soon be forthcoming.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the cape was renamed by King John II of Portugal the *Cape of Good Hope*, because of the optimism engendered by the possibility of a sea route to India, proving false the view that had existed since Ptolemy that the Indian Ocean was land-locked.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Based on later stories of the phantom island known as Bacalao and the carvings on Dighton Rock some have speculated that Portuguese explorer João Vaz Corte-Real discovered Newfoundland in 1473, but the sources are considered unreliable.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal's Iberian rival, Castile, had begun to establish its rule over the Canary Islands in 1402, but became distracted by internal Iberian politics and the repelling of Islamic invasion attempts through most of the 15th century.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the unification of the crowns of Castile and Aragon, an emerging modern Spain became committed to the search for new trade routes overseas.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Crown of Aragon had been an important maritime power, controlling territories in eastern Spain, southwestern France, major islands like Sicily, Malta, and the Kingdom of Naples and Sardinia, with mainland possessions as far as Greece.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1485 and 1488, Columbus had presented the project to king John II of Portugal, who rejected it.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] On 3 August 1492, Columbus departed from Palos de la Frontera.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Land was sighted on 12 October, and Columbus called the island *San Salvador* (Guanahani now in The Bahamas), in what he thought to be the East Indies.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus explored the north coast of Cuba and Hispaniola, by 5 December.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] He was received by the native cacique Guacanagari, who gave him permission to leave some men behind.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus left 39 and founded the settlement of *La Navidad* in what is now Haiti.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Before returning to Spain, he kidnapped 10-25 natives.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Only 7-8 of the 'Indians' arrived alive, but they made an impression on Seville.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] On 15 March 1493, he arrived in Barcelona, where he reported to Isabella and Ferdinand.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Word of his discovery of new lands spread throughout Europe.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus and other Spanish explorers were initially disappointed with their discoveries—unlike Africa or Asia, the Caribbean islanders had little to trade.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The islands thus became the focus of colonization efforts.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] It was not until the continent was explored that Spain found the wealth it had sought.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Shortly after Columbus's return from what would be called the "West Indies", a division of influence became necessary to avoid conflict between the Spaniards and Portuguese.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] It did not mention Portugal, which could not claim newly discovered lands east of the line.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] King John II of Portugal was displeased with the arrangement, feeling it gave him too little land—preventing him from reaching India, his goal.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] He negotiated directly with Ferdinand and Isabella to move the line west, allowing him to claim newly discovered lands east of it.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1494, the Treaty of Tordesillas divided the world between Portugal and Spain.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal gained control over Africa, Asia, and eastern South America (Brazil), encompassing everything outside Europe east of a line drawn 370 leagues west of the Cape Verde islands.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Spaniards received everything west of this line, including the islands discovered by Columbus on his first voyage.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The dividing line, situated about halfway between Portuguese Cape Verde and Spanish discoveries in the Caribbean, split the known world of Atlantic islands evenly.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1500, Pedro Álvares Cabral, initially considering the Brazilian coast as a large island, claimed it for Portugal east of the dividing line.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] This claim was acknowledged by the Spaniards.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral, heading towards India, followed a corridor in the Atlantic negotiated by the treaty for favorable winds.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Later the Spanish territory would prove to include huge areas of the continental mainland of North and South America, though Portuguese-controlled Brazil would expand across the line, and settlements by other European powers ignored the treaty.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Little of the divided area had actually been seen by Europeans, as it was only divided by a geographical definition rather than control on the ground.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The desire to compete with the Ottoman Empire and Columbus's first voyage spurred further maritime exploration and, from 1497, other explorers headed west.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] That year John Cabot (Italian: *Giovanni Caboto*), also a commissioned Italian, got letters patent from King Henry VII of England.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing from Bristol Cabot crossed the Atlantic from a northerly latitude hoping the voyage to the "West Indies" would be shorter and made landfall in North America, possibly Newfoundland.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to Cabot's voyage, the furthest European expeditions in the North Atlantic had been by Norse explorers, who established settlements in Newfoundland and Greenland, which were abandoned in the 11th century and mid-15th century, respectively.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Merchants from Bristol had sponsored exploratory voyages in the 1480s, which did not report anything of note.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1499, João Fernandes Lavrador was licensed by the King of Portugal and together with Pero de Barcelos they first sighted Labrador, which was granted and named after him.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1499 and 1502, the brothers Gaspar and Miguel Corte Real explored and named the coasts of Greenland and Newfoundland.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Both explorations are noted in the 1502 Cantino planisphere.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1497, newly crowned King Manuel I of Portugal sent an exploratory fleet eastwards, fulfilling his predecessor's project of finding a route to the Indies.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In July 1499, news spread that the Portuguese had reached the "true Indies", as a letter was dispatched by the Portuguese king to the Spanish Monarchs.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The third expedition by Columbus in 1498 was the beginning of the first successful Spanish colonization in the West Indies, on the island of Hispaniola.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite growing doubts, Columbus refused to accept he had not reached the Indies.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] He discovered the mouth of the Orinoco River on the north coast of South America and thought the huge quantity of fresh water coming from it could only be from a continental land mass, which he was certain was Asia.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] As shipping between Seville and the West Indies grew, knowledge of the Caribbean islands, Central America and the northern coast of South America increased.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] One of these Spanish fleets, that of Alonso de Ojeda and Amerigo Vespucci in 1499–1500 reached land at the coast of what is now Guyana, where the two seem to have separated in opposite directions.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci sailed southward, discovering the mouth of the Amazon River in July 1499, and reaching 6°S, in present-day north east Brazil, before turning around.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Vicente Yáñez Pinzon was blown off course and reached what is now the northeast coast of Brazil on 26 January 1500, exploring as far south as the present-day state of Pernambuco.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] His fleet was the first to fully enter the Amazon River estuary, which he named *Saint Mary's River of the Freshwater Sea*.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The land was too far east for the Castilians to claim under the Treaty of Tordesillas, but the discovery created Castilian interest, with a second voyage by Pinzon in 1508 (the Pinzón–Solís voyage) and a voyage in 1515–1516 by a navigator of the 1508 expedition, Juan Díaz de Solís.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The 1515–1516 expedition was spurred on by reports of Portuguese exploration of the region.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] It ended when de Solís and some of his crew disappeared when exploring the River Plata in a boat, but what they found reignited Spanish interest, and colonization began in 1531.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In April 1500, the second Portuguese India Armada, headed by Pedro Álvares Cabral, with a crew of expert captains, encountered the Brazilian coast as it swung westward in the Atlantic while performing a large volta do mar to avoid becalming in the Gulf of Guinea.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] On 21 April, a mountain was seen and named *Monte Pascoal*, and on 22 April Cabral landed.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] On 25 April, the entire fleet sailed into the harbour they named *Porto Seguro*.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral perceived that the new land lay east of the line of Tordesillas, and sent an envoy to Portugal with the discovery in letters, including the letter of Pero Vaz de Caminha.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Believing the land to be an island, he named it Ilha de Vera Cruz.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] From the east coast, the fleet then turned eastward towards the southern tip of Africa and India.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral was the first captain to touch four continents, leading the first expedition that connected and united Europe, Africa, the New World, and Asia.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] At the invitation of King Manuel I of Portugal, Amerigo Vespucci participated as an observer in the exploratory voyages to the east coast of South America.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] It was understood that Columbus had not reached Asia but found a new continent, the Americas.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The Americas were named in 1507 by cartographers Martin Waldseemüller and Matthias Ringmann, after Amerigo Vespucci.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1501 to 1502, one of these Portuguese expeditions, led by Gonçalo Coelho, sailed south along the coast of South America to the bay of present-day Rio de Janeiro.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci's account states that the expedition reached the latitude "South Pole elevation 52° S", in the "cold" latitudes of what is now southern Patagonia, before turning back.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci wrote that they headed toward the southwest and south, following "a long, unbending coastline", apparently coincident with the southern South American coast.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] This seems controversial, since he changed part of his description in the subsequent letter, stating a shift, from about 32° S (Southern Brazil) to the south-southeast, to open sea, maintaining that they reached 50°/52° S.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1503, Binot Paulmier de Gonneville, challenging the Portuguese policy of *mare clausum*, led one of the earliest French Normand and Breton expeditions to Brazil.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] He intended to sail to the East Indies, but near the Cape of Good Hope, his ship was diverted to the west by a storm, and landed in the present-day state of Santa Catarina (southern Brazil), on 5 January 1504.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1511 to 1512, Portuguese captains João de Lisboa and Estevão de Fróis reached the River Plata estuary in present-day Uruguay and Argentina, and went as far south as the present-day Gulf of San Matias at 42°S.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition reached a cape extending north to south which they called Cape of "Santa Maria" (Punta del Este); and after 40°S they found a "Cape" or "a point or place extending into the sea", and a "Gulf".
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] After they had navigated for nearly 300 km (186 mi) to round the cape, they again sighted the continent on the other side and steered towards the northwest, but a storm prevented them from making headway.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Driven away by the *Tramontane* or north wind, they retraced their course.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] Christopher de Haro, a Fleming of Sephardic origin, who would serve the Spanish Crown after 1516, believed the navigators had discovered a southern *strait* to west and Asia.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1519, an expedition sent by the Spanish Crown to find a way to Asia was led by the experienced Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleet explored the rivers and bays as it charted the South American coast, until it found a way to the Pacific Ocean through the Strait of Magellan.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1524 to 1525, Aleixo Garcia, a Portuguese conquistador, led a private expedition of shipwrecked Castilian and Portuguese adventurers, who recruited about 2,000 Guaraní Indians.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] They explored the territories of present-day southern Brazil, Paraguay, and Bolivia, using the native trail network, the *Peabiru*.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p01] They were the first Europeans to cross the Chaco and reach the outer territories of the Inca Empire on the hills of the Andes.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p02] Protected from direct Spanish competition by the Treaty of Tordesillas, Portuguese eastward exploration and colonization continued apace.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p02] Twice, in 1485 and 1488, Portugal officially rejected Genoese Christopher Columbus's idea of reaching India by sailing westwards.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p02] King John II of Portugal's experts rejected it, for they held the opinion that Columbus's estimation of a travel distance of 2,400 miles (3,860 km) was low, and in part because Bartolomeu Dias departed in 1487 trying the rounding of the southern tip of Africa.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p02] They believed that sailing east would require a far shorter journey.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p02] Dias's return from the Cape of Good Hope in 1488, and Pero da Covilhã's travel to Ethiopia overland indicated that the richness of the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p02] In July 1497, a small exploratory fleet of four ships and about 170 men left Lisbon under the command of Vasco da Gama.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p02] By December the fleet passed the Great Fish River—where Dias had turned back—and sailed into waters unknown to the Europeans.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p02] Sailing into the Indian Ocean, da Gama entered a maritime region that had three different and well-developed trade circuits.
[src:age-of-discovery/age-of-discovery-p02] The one da Gama encountered connected Mogadishu on the east coast of Africa; Aden, at the tip of the Arabian peninsula; the Persian port of Hormuz; Cambay, in northwestern India; and Calicut, in southwestern India.
